content: He said the same thing he'd been saying for hours... "Burn them all." If that's all, your Grace...

author: jorah mormont
content: The Dothraki don't believe in money. Most of their slaves were given to them as gifts.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: From whom?

author: jorah mormont
content: If you rule a city and you see the horde approaching, you have two choices

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Tell them all to stop.

author: jorah mormont
content: You want the entire horde to stop? For how long?

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Until I command them otherwise.

author: jorah mormont
content: You're learning to talk like a Queen.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Not a Queen. A Khaleesi.

author: viserys targaryen
content: You dare! You give commands to me? To me? You do not command the dragon. I am Lord of the Seven Kingdoms. I don't take orders from savages or their sluts. Do you hear me?

author: irri
content: Rakharo ask if you want him dead, Khaleesi.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: No!

author: irri
content: Rakharo say you should take ear, to teach respect.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Please please, don't hurt him. Tell him I don't want my brother harmed.

author: viserys targaryen
content: Kill these Dothraki dogs! I am your King!

author: jorah mormont
content: Shall we return to the Khalasar, Khaleesi?

author: rakharo
content: You walk. [to Viserys]

author: benjen stark
content: I wanted to be here when you saw it for the first time. I'm leaving this morning.

author: jon snow
content: You're leaving?

author: benjen stark
content: I'm the First Ranger. My job is out there. There have been disturbing reports.

author: jon snow
content: What kind of reports?

author: benjen stark
content: The kind I don't want to believe.

author: jon snow
content: m ready. I won't let you down.

author: benjen stark
content: You're not going. You're no ranger, Jon.

author: jon snow
content: But I'm better than every...

author: benjen stark
content: Better than no one! Here... A man gets what he earns, when he earns it. We'll speak when I return.

author: yoren
content: A bear's balls.

author: tyrion lannister
content: You're joking?

author: yoren
content: And his brains and his guts, his lungs and his heart all fried in his own fat. When you're a hundred miles north of the Wall and you ate your last meal a week ago, you leave nothing for the wolves.

author: tyrion lannister
content: And how do a bear's balls taste?

author: yoren
content: A bit chewy. And what about you, my Lord? What's the strangest thing you've eaten?

author: tyrion lannister
content: Do Dornish girls count? So you roam the Seven Kingdoms, collaring pickpockets and horse thieves and bringing them here as eager recruits?

author: yoren
content: But it's not all of 'em's done bad things. Some of 'em's just poor lads looking for steady feed. Some of 'em's high-born lads looking for glory.

author: tyrion lannister
content: They have a better chance finding feed than glory.

author: benjen stark
content: The Night's Watch is a joke to you, is it? Is that what we are, Lannister? An army of jesters in black?

author: tyrion lannister
content: You don't have enough men to be an army and aside from Yoren here, none of you are particularly funny.

author: benjen stark
content: I hope we've provided you with some good stories to tell when you're back in King's Landing. But something to think about while you're drinking your wine down there, enjoying your brothels... Half the boys you've seen training will die north of the Wall. Might be a wilding's axe that gets them, might be sickness, might just be the cold. They die in pain. And they do it so plump little lords like you can enjoy their summer afternoons in peace and comfort.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Do you think I'm plump? Listen, Benjen... May I call you Benjen?

author: benjen stark
content: Call me what you like.

author: tyrion lannister
content: I'm not sure what I've done to offend you. I have great admiration for the Night's Watch. I've great admiration for you as First Ranger.

author: benjen stark
content: You know, my brother once told me that nothing someone says before the word "but" really counts.

author: tyrion lannister
content: But... I don't believe that giants and ghouls and White Walkers are lurking beyond the Wall. I believe that the only difference between us and the wildlings is that when the Wall went up, our ancestors happened to live on the right side of it.

author: benjen stark
content: You're right. The wildlings are no different from us. A little rougher maybe. But they're made of meat and bone. I know how to track them and I know how to kill them. It's not the wildlings giving me sleepless nights. You've never been north of the Wall, so don't tell me what's out there.

author: yoren
content: Are you going below? Keep well, keep warm.

author: benjen stark
content: Enjoy the capital, brother.

author: yoren
content: I always do.

author: tyrion lannister
content: I think he's starting to like me. "Going below"?

author: yoren
content: Into the tunnel and out the other side. He'll be north of the Wall for a month or two.

author: tyrion lannister
content: So you're heading down to King's Landing too.

author: yoren
content: Day after tomorrow. I get about half of my recruits from their dungeons.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Let's share the road. I could use some decent company.

author: yoren
content: I travel a bit on the grubby side, my Lord.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Not this time. We'll be staying at the finest castles and inns. No one turns away a Lannister.

author: irri
content: Yes, Khaleesi.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: What are you doing?

author: irri
content: When was last time you bleed, Khaleesi? You change, Khaleesi. It's a blessing from the Great Stallion.

author: jorah mormont
content: For a man on horseback, the curved blade is a good thing, easier to handle. It's a good weapon for a Dothrakan. But a man in full plate... the arakh won't get through the steel. That's where the broadsword has the advantage. Designed for piercing plate.

author: rakharo
content: Dothraki don't wear steel dresses.

author: jorah mormont
content: Armor.

author: rakharo
content: Armor. Armor make a man... Vroz?

author: jorah mormont
content: Slow.

author: rakharo
content: Slow.

author: jorah mormont
content: It's true, but it also keeps a man alive.

author: rakharo
content: My father taught me how to fight. He taught me that speed defeats size.

author: jorah mormont
content: I've heard that your father was a famous warrior.

author: rakharo
content: He was bloodrider to Khal Bharbo. And your father, Jorah the Andal? He was a warrior also?

author: jorah mormont
content: He still is. A man of great honor. And I betrayed him.

author: irri
content: The Khaleesi wants to eat something different tonight. Kill some rabbits.

author: rakharo
content: There are no rabbits.

author: irri
content: Find some ducks, she likes ducks.

author: rakharo
content: Have you seen any ducks, woman? No rabbits, no ducks. Do you have eyes in your head? Do you?

author: irri
content: Dog then. I have seen many dogs.

author: jorah mormont
content: I don't think she wants to eat dog.

author: irri
content: The Khaleesi have baby inside her. It is true. She does not bleed for two moons. Her belly start to swell.

author: rakharo
content: A blessing from the Great Stallion.

author: irri
content: She does not want to eat horse.

author: jorah mormont
content: I'll have the boys butcher a goat for supper. I need to ride to Qohor.

author: rhakaro
content: We ride for Vaes Dothrak.

author: jorah mormont
content: Don't worry. I'll catch you. The horde's easy to find.

author: jon snow
content: Don't stand so still. It's harder to hit a moving target. Except for you. You move too much. I could just hold my sword out and let you do the work for me.

author: maester aemon
content: How many winters have you seen, Lord Tyrion?

author: tyrion lannister
content: Eight... no, nine.

author: maester aemon
content: All of them brief?

author: tyrion lannister
content: They say the winter of my birth was three years long, Maester Aemon.

author: maester aemon
content: This summer has lasted nine. But reports from the Citadel tell us the days grow shorter. The Starks are always right eventually

author: jeor mormont
content: We've been capturing wildlings, more every month. They're fleeing south. The ones who flee... say they've seen the White Walkers.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Yes, and the fishermen of Lannisport say they see mermaids.

author: jeor mormont
content: One of our own rangers swore he saw them kill his companions. He swore it right up to the moment Ned Stark chopped his head off.

author: maester aemon
content: The Night's Watch is the only thing standing between the realm and what lies beyond. And it has become an army of undisciplined boys and tired old men. There are less than a thousand of us now. We can't man the other castles on the Wall. We can't properly patrol the wilderness. We've barely enough resources to keep our lads armed and fed.

author: jeor mormont
content: Your sister sits by the side of the King. Tell her we need help.

author: maester aemon
content: When winter does come, gods help us all if we're not ready.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: It's a boy.

author: khal drogo
content: How do you know?

author: daenerys targaryen
content: I know.

author: jon snow
content: I'm sorry to see you leave, Lannister.

author: tyrion lannister
content: It's either me or this cold. And it doesn't appear to be going anywhere.

author: jon snow
content: Will you stop at Winterfell on your way South?

author: tyrion lannister
content: I expect I will. Gods know there aren't many feather beds between here and King's Landing.

author: jon snow
content: If you see my brother Bran, tell him I miss him. Tell him I'd visit if I could.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Of course.

author: jon snow
content: He'll never walk again.

author: tyrion lannister
content: If you're going to be a cripple, it's better to be a rich cripple. Take care, Snow.

author: jon snow
content: Farewell, My Lord.

author: syrio forel
content: You are late, boy. Tomorrow you will be here at midday.

author: arya stark
content: Who are you?

author: syrio forel
content: Your dancing master, Syrio Forel.

author: syrio forel
content: Tomorrow you will catch it. Now pick it up. That is not the way, boy. This is not a great sword that is needing two hands to swing it.

author: arya stark
content: It's too heavy.

author: syrio forel
content: It is heavy as it needs to be to make you strong. Just so. One hand is all that is needed. Now you are standing all wrong. Turn your body side-face. So. You are skinny. That is good. The target is smaller. Now the grip... Let me see. The grip must be delicate.

author: arya stark
content: What if I drop it?

author: syrio forel
content: The steel must be part of your arm. Can you drop part of your arm? No. Nine years Syrio Forel was first sword to the Sealord of Braavos. He knows these things. You must listen to me, boy.

author: arya stark
content: I'm a girl.

author: syrio forel
content: Boy, girl... You are a sword, that is all. That is the grip. You are not holding a battle-axe. You are holding...

author: arya stark
content: A needle.

author: syrio forel
content: Ahhh… Just so. Now we will begin the dance. Remember, child, this is not the dance of the Westeros we are learning... The knight's dance, hacking and hammering. This is the Bravo's dance... The water dance. It is swift and sudden. All men are made of water, do you know this? If you pierce them, the water leaks out and they die. Now you will try to strike me.

author: syrio forel
content: Up! Dead. Dead. Very dead. Come. Again, faster.

author: old nan
content: The little Lordo s been dreaming again.

author: theon greyjoy
content: We have visitors.

author: bran stark
content: I don't want to see anyone.

author: theon greyjoy
content: Really? If I was cooped up all day with no one but this old bat for company, I'd go mad. Anyway, you don't have a choice. Robb's waiting.

author: bran stark
content: I don't want to go.

author: theon greyjoy
content: Neither do I. But Robb's Lord of Winterfell, which means I do what he says and you do what I say. Hodor! Help Bran down the hall.

author: tyrion lannister
content: I must say I received a slightly warmer welcome on my last visit.

author: robb stark
content: Any man of the Night's Watch is welcome at Winterfell.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Any man of the Night's Watch, but not I, eh, boy?

author: robb stark
content: I'm not your boy, Lannister. I'm Lord of Winterfell while my father is away.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Then you might learn a lordo s courtesy.

author: tyrion lannister
content: So it's true. Hello Bran. Do you remember anything about what happened?

author: maester luwin
content: He has no memory of that day.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Curious.

author: robb stark
content: Why are you here?

author: tyrion lannister
content: Would your charming companion be so kind as to kneel? My neck is beginning to hurt.

author: bran stark
content: Kneel, Hodor.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Do you like to ride, Bran?

author: bran stark
content: Yes. Well, I mean I did like to.

author: maester luwin
content: The boy has lost the use of his legs.

author: tyrion lannister
content: What of it? With the right horse and saddle, even a cripple can ride.

author: bran stark
content: I'm not a cripple.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Then I'm not a dwarf. My father will rejoice to hear it. I have a gift for you. Give that to your saddler. He'll provide the rest. You must shape the horse to the rider. Start with a yearling and teach it to respond to the reins and to the boy's voice.

author: bran stark
content: Will I really be able to ride?

author: tyrion lannister
content: You will. On horseback you will be as tall as any of them.

author: robb stark
content: Is this some kind of trick? Why do you want to help him?

author: tyrion lannister
content: I have a tender spot in my heart for cripples, bastards and broken things.

author: robb stark
content: You've done my brother a kindness. The hospitality of Winterfell is yours.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Spare me your false courtesies, Lord Stark. There's a brothel outside your walls. There I'll find a bed and both of us can sleep easier.

author: theon greyjoy
content: Couldn't resist some northern ass? If you like redheads, ask for Ros.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Come to see me off, Greyjoy? Kind of you. Your master doesn't seem to like Lannisters.

author: theon greyjoy
content: He's not my master.

author: tyrion lannister
content: No, of course not. What happened here? Where is lady Stark? Why didn't she receive me?

author: theon greyjoy
content: She wasn't feeling well.

author: tyrion lannister
content: She's not in Winterfell, is she? Where did she go?

author: theon greyjoy
content: My lady's whereabouts...

author: tyrion lannister
content: My lady? Your loyalty to your captors is touching. Tell me, how do you think Balon Greyjoy would feel if he could see his only surviving son has turned lackey? I still remember seeing my father's fleet burn in Lannisport. I believe your uncles were responsible?

author: theon greyjoy
content: Must have been a pretty sight.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Nothing prettier than watching sailors burn alive. Yes, a great victory for your people. Shame how it all turned out.

author: theon greyjoy
content: We were outnumbered 10 to one.

author: tyrion lannister
content: A stupid rebellion then. I suppose your father realized that when your brothers died in battle. Now here you are, your enemy's squire.

author: theon greyjoy
content: Careful, Imp.

author: tyrion lannister
content: I've offended you. Forgive me, it's been a rough morning. Anyway, don't despair. I'm a constant disappointment to my own father and I've learned to live with it. Your next tumble with Ros is on me. I'll try not to wear her out.

author: jon snow
content: Leg, shoulder, leg. Left foot forward. Good. Now pivot as you deliver the stroke. Put all your weight behind it.

author: grenn
content: What in seven hells is that?

author: pyp
content: They'll need an eighth hell to fit him in.

author: alliser thorne
content: Tell them your name.

author: sam tarly
content: Samwell Tarly, of Horn Hill. I mean, I was of Horn Hill. I've come to take the black.

author: rast
content: Come to take the black pudding.

author: alliser thorne
content: Well, you couldn't be any worse than you look. See what he can do.

author: sam tarly
content: I yield. Please, no more.

author: alliser thorne
content: On your feet. Pick up your sword. Hit him till he finds his feet. It seems they've run short of poachers and thieves down south. Now they send us squealing bloody pigs. Again, harder.

author: jon snow
content: Enough! He yielded.

author: alliser thorne
content: Looks like the bastardo s in love. All right then, lord Snow, you wish to defend your lady love, let's make it an exercise. You two. Three of you ought to be sufficient to make lady piggy squeal. All you've got to do is get past the bastard.

author: jon snow
content: Are you sure you want to do this?

author: grenn
content: No. Yield yield yield! I yield.

author: alliser thorne
content: We're done for today. Go clean the armory. That's all you're good for.

author: pyp
content: Well fought!

author: grenn
content: Piss off.

author: sam tarly
content: Did he hurt you?

author: jon snow
content: I've had worse.

author: sam tarly
content: You can call me Sam... If you want. My mother calls me Sam.

author: jon snow
content: It's not going to get any easier, you know? You'll have to defend yourself.

author: grenn
content: Why didn't you get up and fight?

author: sam tarly
content: I wanted to. I just couldn't.

author: grenn
content: Why not?

author: sam tarly
content: I'm a coward. My father always says so.

author: jon snow
content: The Wall's no place for cowards.

author: sam tarly
content: You're right. I'm sorry. I just... Wanted to thank you.

author: grenn
content: A bloody coward. People saw us talking to him. Now they'll think we're cowards too.

author: pyp
content: You're too stupid to be a coward.

author: grenn
content: You're too stupid to be a...

author: pyp
content: Quick now, before summer's over.

author: grenn
content: Come on here!

author: jorah mormont
content: Vaes Dothrak. The city of the horselords.

author: viserys targaryen
content: A pile of mud. Mud and shit and twigs - best these savages can do.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: These are my people now. You shouldn't call them savages.

author: viserys targaryen
content: I'll call them what I like, because they're my people. This is my army. Khal Drogo is marching the wrong way with my army.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: If my brother was given an army of Dothraki, could you conquer the Seven Kingdoms?

author: jorah mormont
content: The Dothraki have never crossed the Narrow Sea. They fear any water their horses can't drink.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: But if they did?

author: jorah mormont
content: King Robert is fool enough to meet them in open battle, but the men advising him are different.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: And you know these men?

author: jorah mormont
content: I fought beside them once, long ago. Now Ned Stark wants my head. He drove me from my land.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: You sold slaves.

author: jorah mormont
content: Aye.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Why?

author: jorah mormont
content: I had no money and an expensive wife.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: And where is she now?

author: jorah mormont
content: In another place, with another man.

author: doreah
content: Your Grace?

author: viserys targaryen
content: Yes, my dear?

author: doreah
content: They call you the last dragon...

author: viserys targaryen
content: They do.

author: doreah
content: You have dragon's blood in your veins?

author: viserys targaryen
content: It's entirely possible.

author: doreah
content: What happened to the dragons? I was told that brave men killed them all.

author: viserys targaryen
content: The brave men didn't kill dragons. The brave men rode them. Rode them from Valyria to build the greatest civilization this world has ever seen. The breath of the greatest dragon forged the Iron Throne, which the Usurper is keeping warm for me. The swords of the vanquished, a thousand of them... melted together like so many candles.

author: doreah
content: I have always wanted to see a dragon. There is nothing in the world that I would rather see.

author: viserys targaryen
content: Really? Why dragons?

author: doreah
content: They can fly. And wherever they are, just a few flaps of their wings and they're somewhere else... Far away. And they can kill. Anyone or anything that tries to hurt them gets burned away to nothing... melted... like so many candles. Seeing a dragon would make me very happy.

author: viserys targaryen
content: Well, after 15 years in a pleasure house, I imagine just seeing the sky makes you happy.

author: doreah
content: I was not locked in. I have seen things.

author: viserys targaryen
content: What have you seen?

author: doreah
content: I've seen... A man from Asshai with a dagger of real dragonglass. I've seen a man who could change his face the way that other men change their clothes. And I've seen a pirate who wore his weight in gold and whose ship had sails of colored silk. So... Have you seen one?

author: viserys targaryen
content: A pirate ship?

author: doreah
content: A dragon.

author: viserys targaryen
content: No, the last one died many years before I was born. I'll tell you what I have seen

author: doreah
content: What happened to the skulls?

author: viserys targaryen
content: I don't know. The Usurper had them smashed to powder, I expect. Scattered to the wind.

author: doreah
content: That's very sad.

author: viserys targaryen
content: Yes, it is. What did I buy you for? To make me sad?

author: doreah
content: No, your Grace. To teach your sister.

author: viserys targaryen
content: To teach my sister how to be a better lover? You think I bought you to make Khal Drogo happy? You pretty little idiot. Go on then. Get on with it.

author: septa mordane
content: Someday your husband will sit there and you will sit by his side. And one day, before too long, you will present your son to the court. All the lords of Westeros will gather here to see the little prince...

author: sansa stark
content: What if I have a girl?

author: septa mordane
content: Gods be good, you'll have boys and girls and plenty of them.

author: sansa stark
content: What if I only have girls?

author: septa mordane
content: I wouldn't worry about that.

author: sansa stark
content: Jeyne Poole's mother had five children, all of them girls.

author: septa mordane
content: Yes, but it's highly unlikely.

author: sansa stark
content: But what if?

author: septa mordane
content: If you only had girls, I suppose the throne would pass to Prince Joffrey's little brother.

author: sansa stark
content: And everyone would hate me.

author: septa mordane
content: Nobody could ever hate you.

author: sansa stark
content: Joffrey does.

author: septa mordane
content: Nonsense. Why would you say such a thing? That business with the wolves? I've told you a hundred times... A direwolf is not...

author: sansa stark
content: Please shut up about it.

author: septa mordane
content: Do you remember your lessons? Who built the Iron Throne?

author: sansa stark
content: Aegon the Conqueror.

author: septa mordane
content: And who built the Red Keep?

author: sansa stark
content: Maegor the Cruel.

author: septa mordane
content: And how many years did it take to build...

author: sansa stark
content: My grandfather and uncle were murdered here, weren't they?

author: septa mordane
content: They were killed on the orders of King Aerys, yes.

author: sansa stark
content: The Mad King.

author: septa mordane
content: Commonly known as the Mad King.

author: sansa stark
content: Why were they killed?

author: septa mordane
content: You should speak to your father about these matters.

author: sansa stark
content: I don't want to speak to my father, ever.

author: septa mordane
content: You will find it in your heart to forgive your father.

author: sansa stark
content: No, I won't.

author: janos slynt
content: It's the Hando s tournament that's causing all this trouble, my Lords.

author: eddard stark
content: The King's tournament. I assure you the Hand wants no part of it.

author: janos slynt
content: Call it what you will, Lord Stark Ser, the city is packed with people and more flooding in every day. Last night we had a tavern riot, a brothel fire, three stabbings and a drunken horse race down the Street of Sisters.

author: varys
content: Dreadful.

author: renly baratheon
content: If you can't keep the King's peace, perhaps the City Watch should be commanded by someone who can.

author: janos slynt
content: I need more men.

author: eddard stark
content: You'll get 50. Lord Baelish will see it paid for.

author: petyr baelish
content: I will?

author: eddard stark
content: You found money for a champion's purse, you can find money to keep the peace. I'll also give you 20 of my household guards till the crowds have left.

author: janos slynt
content: Thank you, my Lord Hand Ser. They will be put to good use.

author: eddard stark
content: The sooner this is over, the better.

author: varys
content: The realm prospers from such events, my Lord. They give the great a chance at glory, and the lowly a respite from their woes.

author: petyr baelish
content: And every inn in the city is full and the whores are walking bow-legged.

author: eddard stark
content: I'm sure the tourney puts coins in many a pocket. Now... If there's nothing else, my Lords?

author: grand maester pycelle
content: This heat. On days like this, I envy you northerners your summer snows. Until tomorrow my Lord.

author: eddard stark
content: I've been hoping to talk to you about Jon Arryn.

author: grand maester pycelle
content: Lord Arryn? His death was a great sadness to all of us. I took personal charge of his care, but I could not save him. His sickness struck him very hard and very fast. I saw him in my chambers just the night before he passed. Lord Jon often came to me for counsel.

author: eddard stark
content: Why?

author: grand maester pycelle
content: I have been Grand Maester for many years. Kings and Hands have come to me for advice since...

author: eddard stark
content: What did Jon want the night before he died?

author: grand maester pycelle
content: He came inquiring after a book.

author: eddard stark
content: A book? What book?

author: grand maester pycelle
content: I fear it would be of little interest to you, my Lord. A ponderous tome.

author: eddard stark
content: I'd like to read it.

author: grand maester pycelle
content: The lineages and histories of the great houses of the Seven Kingdoms, with descriptions of many high lords and noble ladies and their children.

author: eddard stark
content: Harkon Umber, first of his name, born to lord Hother Umber and lady Amaryllis Umber in the 183rd year after Aegon's landing, at the last hearth. Blue of eye, brown of hair and fair complected, died in his 14th year of a wound sustained

author: grand maester pycelle
content: As I said, my Lord, a ponderous read.

author: eddard stark
content: Did Jon Arryn tell you what he wanted with it?

author: grand maester pycelle
content: He did not, my Lord. And I did not presume to ask.

author: eddard stark
content: Jon's death...

author: grand maester pycelle
content: Such a tragedy.

author: eddard stark
content: Did he say anything to you during his final hours?

author: grand maester pycelle
content: Nothing of import, my Lord. There was one phrase he kept repeating

author: eddard stark
content: The seed is strong"? What does that mean?

author: grand maester pycelle
content: The dying mind is a demented mind, Lord Stark. For all the weight they're given, last words are usually as significant as first words.

author: eddard stark
content: And you're quite certain he died of a natural illness?

author: grand maester pycelle
content: What else could it be?

author: eddard stark
content: Poison.

author: grand maester pycelle
content: A disturbing thought. I don't think it likely. The Hand was loved by all. What sort of man would dare...

author: eddard stark
content: I've heard it said that poison is a woman's weapon.

author: grand maester pycelle
content: Yes. Women, cravens... and eunuchs. Did you know that lord Varys is a eunuch?

author: eddard stark
content: Everybody knows that.

author: grand maester pycelle
content: Yes, yes, of course. How that sort of person found himself on the King's Council, I will never know.

author: eddard stark
content: I've taken enough of your time.

author: grand maester pycelle
content: No trouble at all, my Lord. It's a great honor...

author: eddard stark
content: Thank you. I'll find my own way out.

author: arya stark
content: Syrio says a water dancer can stand on one toe for hours.

author: eddard stark
content: It's a hard fall down these steps.

author: arya stark
content: Syrio says every hurt is a lesson and every lesson makes you better. Tomorrow I'm going to be chasing cats.

author: eddard stark
content: Cats? Syrio says…

author: arya stark
content: He says every swordsman should study cats. They're quiet as shadows and as light as feathers. You have to be quick to catch them.

author: eddard stark
content: He's right about that.

author: arya stark
content: Now that Bran's awake will he come live with us?

author: eddard stark
content: He needs to get his strength back first.

author: arya stark
content: He wants to be a knight of the King's Guard. He can't be one now, can he?

author: eddard stark
content: No. But someday he could be Lord of a holdfast or sit on the King's Council. Or he might raise castles like Brandon the Builder.

author: arya stark
content: Can I be Lord of a holdfast?

author: eddard stark
content: You will marry a high Lord and rule his castle. And your sons shall be knights and princes and lords.

author: arya stark
content: No. That's not me.

author: sam tarly
content: Hello. Ser Alliser said I'm to be your new watch partner. I should warn you, I don't see all that well.

author: jon snow
content: Come stand by the fire. It's warmer.

author: sam tarly
content: No, that's all right. I'm fine.

author: jon snow
content: You're not. You're freezing.

author: sam tarly
content: I don't like high places.

author: jon snow
content: You can't fight. You can't see. You're afraid of heights and almost everything else probably. What are you doing here, Sam?

author: sam tarly
content: On the morning of my 18th nameday, my father came to me. "You're almost a man now," he said, "but you're not worthy of my land and title. Tomorrow, you're going to take the black, forsake all claim to your inheritance and start north. If you do not," he said, "then we'll have a hunt and somewhere in these woods your horse will stumble and you'll be thrown from your saddle to die. Or so I'll tell your mother. Nothing would please me more." Ser Alliser's going to make me fight again tomorrow, isn't he?

author: jon snow
content: Yes, he is.

author: sam tarly
content: I'm not going to get any better, you know?

author: jon snow
content: Well… You can't get any worse.

author: petyr baelish
content: I hear you're reading a boring book.

author: eddard stark
content: Pycelle talks too much.

author: petyr baelish
content: He never stops. Do you know Ser Hugh of the Vale? Not surprising. Until recently, he was only a squire... Jon Arryn's squire. He was knighted almost immediately after his master's untimely death.

author: eddard stark
content: Knighted for what? Why are you telling me this?

author: petyr baelish
content: I promised Cat that I'd help you.

author: eddard stark
content: Where is Ser Hugh? I'll speak to him.

author: petyr baelish
content: A singularly bad idea. Do you see that boy there? One of Varys's little birds. The Spider has taken a great interest in your comings and goings. Now look there. That one belongs to the Queen. And do you see that Septa pretending to read her book?

author: eddard stark
content: Varys or the Queen?

author: petyr baelish
content: No. She's one of mine. Is there someone in your service whom you trust completely?

author: eddard stark
content: Yes.

author: petyr baelish
content: The wiser answer was no, my Lord. Get a message to this paragon of yours... Discreetly. Send him to question Ser Hugh. After that, you might want him to visit a certain armorer in the city. He lives in a large house at the top of the street of Steel.

author: petyr baelish
content: I have my observers, as I said, and it's possible that they saw Lord Arryn visit this armorer several times in the weeks before his death.

author: eddard stark
content: Lord Baelish, perhaps I was wrong to distrust you.

author: petyr baelish
content: Distrusting me was the wisest thing you've done since you climbed off your horse.

author: jory cassel
content: Ser Hugh? Ser Hugh!

author: hugh of vale
content: As you can see, I'm busy.

author: jory cassel
content: I'm here on behalf of Lord Eddard Stark, the Hand of the king. I'm the captain of his guard.

author: hugh of vale
content: I'm sorry. I didn't catch your name, Ser...

author: jory cassel
content: No "ser." I'm not a knight.

author: hugh of vale
content: I see. Well, it just so happens that I am.

author: jory cassel
content: He said he'd be glad to talk to the Hand himself. He's a knight, you see.

author: eddard stark
content: A knight. They strut around like roosters down here. Even the ones who've never seen an arrow coming their way.

author: jory cassel
content: You shouldn't be out here, my Lord. There's no telling who has eyes where.

author: eddard stark
content: Let them look.

author: tobho mott
content: The former Hand did call on me, my Lord, several times. I regret to say he did not honor me with his patronage.

author: eddard stark
content: What did Lord Arryn want?

author: tobho mott
content: He always came to see the boy.

author: eddard stark
content: I'd like to see him as well.

author: tobho mott
content: As you wish, my Lord. Gendry! Here he is. Strong for his age. He works hard. Show the Hand the helmet you made, lad.

author: eddard stark
content: This is fine work.

author: gendry baratheon
content: It's not for sale.

author: tobho mott
content: Boy, this is the King's Hand! If his lordship wants the helmet...

author: gendry baratheon
content: I made it for me.

author: tobho mott
content: Forgive him, my Lord.

author: eddard stark
content: There's nothing to forgive. When Lord Arryn came to visit you, what would you talk about?

author: gendry baratheon
content: He just asked me questions is all, my Lord.

author: eddard stark
content: What kind of questions?

author: gendry baratheon
content: About my work at first, if I was being treated well, if I liked it here. But then he started asking me about my mother.

author: eddard stark
content: Your mother?

author: gendry baratheon
content: Who she was, what she looked like.

author: eddard stark
content: What did you tell him?

author: gendry baratheon
content: She died when I was little. She had yellow hair. She'd sing to me sometimes.

author: eddard stark
content: Look at me. Get back to work, lad. If the day ever comes when that boy'd rather wield a sword than forge one, you send him to me.

author: jory cassel
content: Find anything?

author: eddard stark
content: King Robert's bastard son.

author: jory cassel
content: This is for the King from Lord Stark.

author: jaime lannister
content: Listen. Do you hear them? How many do you think are in there with him? Guess.

author: jory cassel
content: Three? Four?

author: jaime lannister
content: He likes to do this when I'm on duty... He makes me listen as he insults my sister.

author: jory cassel
content: Forgive me, my Lord...

author: jaime lannister
content: Why do I have to forgive you? Have you wronged me?

author: jory cassel
content: We've met before, you know.

author: jaime lannister
content: Have we? Strange, I've forgotten.

author: jory cassel
content: The siege of Pyke. We fought side by side one afternoon.

author: jaime lannister
content: That's where you got your scar?

author: jory cassel
content: Aye. One of the Greyjoys nearly took my eye.

author: jaime lannister
content: Vicious sons of whores.

author: jory cassel
content: They like their bloodshed.

author: jaime lannister
content: They stopped liking it at the end. That was a proper battle. D'you remember Thoros of Myr charging through the breach?

author: jory cassel
content: With his burning sword? I'll remember that till the day I die.

author: jaime lannister
content: I saw the youngest of the Greyjoy lads at Winterfell. It was like seeing a shark on a mountaintop.

author: jory cassel
content: Theon? He's a good lad.

author: jaime lannister
content: I doubt it.

author: robert baratheon
content: I'll bet you smell of blackberry jam! Let me smell it. Come here.

author: jory cassel
content: Can I leave this with you? The message from Lord Stark.

author: jaime lannister
content: I don't serve Lord Stark.

author: grenn
content: Where have you been?

author: jon snow
content: Watch duty. With Sam.

author: pyp
content: Prince Porkchop. Where is he?

author: jon snow
content: He wasn't hungry.

author: pyp
content: Impossible!

author: jon snow
content: That's enough. Sam's no different from the rest of us. There was no place for him in the world, so he's come here. We're not going to hurt him in the training yard anymore. Never again, no matter what Thorne says. He's our brother now and we're going to protect him.

author: rast
content: You are in love, Lord Snow. You girls can do as you please. But if Thorne puts me up against Lady Piggy, I'm gonna slice me off a side of bacon.

author: jon snow
content: No one touches Sam.

author: alliser thorne
content: What are you waiting for? Attack him! You, get in there.

author: grenn
content: Hit me. Go on, hit me! I yield! Yield yield. I yield.

author: alliser thorne
content: You think this is funny, do you? When you're out there beyond the Wall with the sun going down, do you want a man at your back? Or a sniveling boy?

author: viserys targaryen
content: You send this whore to give me commands? I should have sent you back her head!

author: doreah
content: Forgive me, Khaleesi. I did as you asked.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Hush now. It's all right. Irri, take her and leave us.

author: irri
content: Yes, Khaleesi.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Why did you hit her?!

author: viserys targaryen
content: How many times do I have to tell you? You do not command me.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: I wasn't commanding you. I just wanted to invite you to supper.

author: viserys targaryen
content: What's this?

author: daenerys targaryen
content: It's a gift. I had it made for you.

author: viserys targaryen
content: Dothraki rags? Are you going to dress me now?

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Please.

author: viserys targaryen
content: This stinks of manure. All of it.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Stop - stop it.

author: viserys targaryen
content: You would turn me into one of them, wouldn't you? Next you'll want to braid my hair.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: You've no right to a braid. You've won no victories yet.

author: viserys targaryen
content: You do not talk back to me!

author: viserys targaryen
content: You are a horselordo s slut. And now you've woken the dragon...

author: daenerys targaryen
content: I am a Khaleesi of the Dothraki! I am the wife of the great Khal and I carry his son inside me. The next time you raise a hand to me will be the last time you have hands.

author: sam tarly
content: I know for a fact that some of the officers go to that brothel in Mole's Town.

author: jon snow
content: I wouldn't doubt it.

author: sam tarly
content: Don't you think it's a little bit unfair? Making us take our vows while they sneak off for a little sally on the side?

author: jon snow
content: Sally on the side?

author: sam tarly
content: It's silly, isn't it? What, we can't defend the Wall unless we're celibate? It's absurd.

author: jon snow
content: I didn't think you'd be so upset about it.

author: sam tarly
content: Why not? Because I'm fat? But I like girls just as much as you do. They might not like me as much. I've never... been with one. You've probably had hundreds.

author: jon snow
content: As a matter of fact, I'm the same as you.

author: sam tarly
content: I find that hard to believe.

author: jon snow
content: I came very close once. I was alone in a room with a naked girl, but...

author: sam tarly
content: You didn't know where to put it?

author: jon snow
content: I know where to put it.

author: sam tarly
content: Was she... Old and ugly?

author: jon snow
content: Young and gorgeous. A whore named Ros.

author: sam tarly
content: What color hair?

author: jon snow
content: Red.

author: sam tarly
content: I like red hair. And her... Her...

author: jon snow
content: You don't want to know.

author: sam tarly
content: That good?

author: jon snow
content: Better.

author: sam tarly
content: Oh no. So why exactly did you not make love to Ros with the perfect...

author: jon snow
content: What's my name?

author: sam tarly
content: Jon Snow?

author: jon snow
content: And why is my surname Snow?

author: sam tarly
content: Because... You're a bastard from the north.

author: jon snow
content: I never met my mother. My father wouldn't even tell me her name. I don't know if she's living or dead. I don't know if she's a noblewoman or a fisherman's wife... Or a whore. So I sat there in the brothel as Ros took off her clothes. But I couldn't do it. Because all I could think was what if I got her pregnant and she had a child, another bastard named Snow? It's not a good life for a child.

author: sam tarly
content: So... You didn't know where to put it?

author: alliser thorne
content: Enjoying yourselves? You look cold, boys.

author: sam tarly
content: It is a bit nippy.

author: alliser thorne
content: A bit nippy, yeah, by the fire, indoors. It's still summer. Do you boys even remember the last winter? How long has it been now? What, 10 years? I remember. Was it uncomfortable at Winterfell? Were there days when you just couldn't get warm, never mind how many fires your servants built?

author: jon snow
content: I build my own fires.

author: alliser thorne
content: That's admirable. I spent six months out there, beyond the Wall during the last winter. It was supposed to be a two-week mission. We heard a rumor Mance Rayder was planning to attack Eastwatch. So we went out to look for some of his men... Capture them, gather some knowledge. The Wildlings who fight for Mance Rayder are hard men. Harder than you'll ever be. They know their country better than we do. They knew there was a storm coming in. So they hid in their caves and waited for it to pass. And we got caught in the open. Wind so strong it yanked 100-foot trees straight from the ground, roots and all. If you took your gloves off to find your cock to have a piss, you lost a finger to the frost. And all in darkness. You don't know cold. Neither of you do. The horses died first. We didn't have enough to feed them, to keep them warm. Eating the horses was easy. But later when we started to fall... That wasn't easy. We should have had a couple of boys like you along, shouldn't we? Soft, fat boys like you. We'd have lasted a fortnight on you and still had bones leftover for soup. Soon we'll have new recruits and you lot will be passed along to the Lord Commander for assignment and they will call you men of the Night's Watch, but you'd be fools to believe it. You're boys still. And come the winter you will die... Like flies.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: I hit him. I hit the dragon.

author: jorah mormont
content: Your brother Rhaegar was the last dragon. Viserys is less than the shadow of a snake.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: He is still the true King.

author: jorah mormont
content: The truth now

author: daenerys targaryen
content: No. But the common people are waiting for him. Illyrio said they're sewing dragon banners and praying for his return.

author: jorah mormont
content: The common people pray for rain, health and a summer that never ends. They don't care what games the high Lords play.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: What do you pray for, Ser Jorah?

author: jorah mormont
content: Home.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: I pray for home too. My brother will never take back the Seven Kingdoms. He couldn't lead an army even if my husband gave him one. He'll never take us home.

author: petyr baelish
content: Lover's quarrel?

author: sansa stark
content: I'm sorry. Do I...?

author: septa mordane
content: Sansa dear, this is Lord Baelish. He's known...

author: petyr baelish
content: An old friend of the family. I've known your mother a long long time.

author: arya stark
content: Why do they call you Littlefinger?

author: sansa stark
content: Arya!

author: septa mordane
content: Don't be rude!

author: petyr baelish
content: No, it's quite all right. When I was a child I was very small and I come from a little spit of land called The Fingers, so you see, it's an exceedingly clever nickname.

author: robert baratheon
content: I've been sitting here for days! Start the damn joust before I piss myself!

author: sansa stark
content: Gods, who is that?

author: petyr baelish
content: Ser Gregor Clegane. They call him the Mountain. The Houndo s older brother.

author: sansa stark
content: And his opponent?

author: petyr baelish
content: Ser Hugh of the Vale. He was Jon Arryn's squire. Look how far he's come.

author: robert baratheon
content: Yes, yes. Enough of the bloody pomp. Have at it!

author: petyr baelish
content: Not what you were expecting? Has anyone ever told you the story of the Mountain and the Hound? Lovely little tale of brotherly love. The Hound was just a pup, six years old maybe. Gregor a few years older, already a big lad, already getting a bit of a reputation. Some lucky boys just born with a talent for violence. One evening... Gregor found his little brother playing with a toy by the fire... Gregor's toy, a wooden knight. Gregor never said a word, he just grabbed his brother by the scruff of his neck and shoved his face into the burning coals. Held him there while the boy screamed, while his face melted. There aren't very many people who know that story.

author: sansa stark
content: I won't tell anyone. I promise.

author: petyr baelish
content: No, please don't. If the Hound so much as heard you mention it, I'm afraid all the knights in King's Landing would not be able to save you.

author: jory cassel
content: My Lord, Her Grace the Queen.

author: eddard stark
content: Your Grace.

author: cersei lannister
content: You're missing your tournament.

author: eddard stark
content: Putting my name on it doesn't make it mine.

author: cersei lannister
content: I thought we might put what happened on the Kingsroad behind us – the ugliness with the wolves. And forcing you to kill the beast was extreme. Though sometimes we go to extremes where our children are concerned. How is Sansa?

author: eddard stark
content: She likes it here.

author: cersei lannister
content: The only Stark who does. Favors her mother, not much of the north in her.

author: eddard stark
content: What are you doing here?

author: cersei lannister
content: I might ask the same of you. What is it you hope to accomplish?

author: eddard stark
content: The King called on me to serve him and the realm, and that's what I'll do until he tells me otherwise.

author: cersei lannister
content: You can't change him. You can't help him. He'll do what he wants, which is all he's ever done. You'll try your best to pick up the pieces.

author: eddard stark
content: If that's my job, then so be it.

author: cersei lannister
content: You're just a soldier, aren't you? You take your orders and you carry on. I suppose it makes sense. Your older brother was trained to lead and you were trained to follow.

author: eddard stark
content: I was also trained to kill my enemies, Your Grace.

author: cersei lannister
content: As was I.

author: marillion
content: Seven blessings to you, goodfolk!

author: catelyn stark
content: And to you.

author: rodrick cassel
content: Boy! Bread, meat and beer, quickly.

author: marillion
content: Good idea, grandfather. I'm starving. A song while we wait or?

author: rodrick cassel
content: I'd rather throw myself down a well.

author: marillion
content: Grandfather, may be your last chance if you're heading north. The only music the northerners know is the howling of wolves!

author: masha heddle
content: I'm sorry, my Lord, we're full up. Every room.

author: tyrion lannister
content: My men can sleep in the stable. As for myself, I don't require a large room.

author: masha heddle
content: Truly, my lord, we have nothing.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Is there nothing I can do... to remedy this?

author: bronn
content: You can have my room.

author: tyrion lannister
content: There's a clever man. You can manage food, I trust? Yoren, dine with me.

author: yoren
content: Aye, my Lord.

author: marillion
content: My Lord of Lannister! Might I entertain you while you eat? I can sing of your father's victory at King's Landing!

author: tyrion lannister
content: Nothing would more likely ruin my supper. Lady Stark! What an unexpected pleasure. I was sorry to have missed you at Winterfell.

author: masha heddle
content: Lady Stark.

author: catelyn stark
content: I was still Catelyn Tully the last time I stayed here. You, Ser... Is that the black bat of Harrenhal I see embroidered on your coat?

author: knight of house whent
content: It is, my Lady.

author: catelyn stark
content: And is Lady Whent a true and honest friend to my father... Lord Hoster Tully of Riverrun?

author: knight of house whent
content: She is.

author: catelyn stark
content: The red stallion was always a welcome sight at Riverrun. My father counts Jonas Bracken amongst his oldest and most loyal bannermen.

author: knight of house bracken
content: Our lord is honored by his trust.

author: tyrion lannister
content: I envy your father all his fine friends, but I don't quite see the purpose of this.

author: catelyn stark
content: Knight of House Frey

author: catelyn stark
content: This man... Came into my house as a guest and there conspired to murder my son, a boy of 10. In the name of King Robert and the good Lords you serve, I call upon you to seize him and help me return him to Winterfell to await the king's justice.

author: eddard stark
content: Does Ser Hugh have any family in the capital?

author: barristan selmy
content: No. I stood vigil for him myself last night. He had no one else.

author: eddard stark
content: He'd never worn this armor before.

author: barristan selmy
content: Bad luck for him... Going against the Mountain.

author: eddard stark
content: Who determines the draw?

author: barristan selmy
content: All the knights draw straws, Lord Stark.

author: eddard stark
content: Aye... But who holds the straws? You've done good work, Sisters.

author: barristan selmy
content: Life is strange. Not so many years ago we fought as enemies at the Trident.

author: eddard stark
content: I'm glad we never met on the field, Ser Barristan... as is my wife. I don't think the widow's life would suit her.

author: barristan selmy
content: You're too modest. I've seen you cut down a dozen great knights.

author: eddard stark
content: My father once told me you were the best he'd ever seen. I never knew the man to be wrong about matters of combat.

author: barristan selmy
content: He was a fine man, your father. What the Mad King did to him was a terrible crime.

author: eddard stark
content: And that lad... He was a squire until a few months ago. How could he afford a new suit of armor?

author: barristan selmy
content: Perhaps Lord Arryn left him some money? I hear the King wants to joust today.

author: eddard stark
content: Yes. That will never happen.

author: barristan selmy
content: Robert tends to do what he wants.

author: eddard stark
content: If the King got what he wanted all the time, we'd still be fighting a damned rebellion.

author: lancel lannister
content: It's made too small, Your Grace. It won't go.

author: robert baratheon
content: Your mother was a dumb whore with a fat arse. Did you know that? Look at this idiot! One ball and no brains. He can't even put a man's armor on him properly.

author: eddard stark
content: You're too fat for your armor.

author: robert baratheon
content: Fat? Fat, is it? Is that how you speak to your King? That was funny, is it?

author: robert baratheon
content: Oh, it's funny, is it?

author: lancel lannister
content: No, Your Grace.

author: robert baratheon
content: No? You don't like the Hando s joke?

author: eddard stark
content: You're torturing the poor boy.

author: robert baratheon
content: You heard the Hand. The King's too fat for his armor! Go find the breastplate stretcher, now!

author: eddard stark
content: The breastplate stretcher?

author: robert baratheon
content: How long before he figures it out?

author: eddard stark
content: Maybe you should have one invented.

author: robert baratheon
content: All right, all right. But you watch me out there. I still know how to point a lance.

author: eddard stark
content: You have no business jousting. Leave that for the young men.

author: robert baratheon
content: Why? Because I'm king? Piss on that. I want to hit somebody!

author: eddard stark
content: And who's going to hit you back?

author: robert baratheon
content: Anybody who can. And the last man in his saddle... will be you!

author: eddard stark
content: There's not a man in the Seven Kingdoms would risk hurting you.

author: robert baratheon
content: Are you telling me those cowards would let me win?

author: eddard stark
content: Aye.

author: robert baratheon
content: Drink.

author: eddard stark
content: I'm not thirsty.

author: robert baratheon
content: Drink. Your King commands it. Gods! Too fat for my armor.

author: eddard stark
content: Your squire... A Lannister boy?

author: robert baratheon
content: Hmm... A bloody idiot... But Cersei insisted. I have Jon Arryn to thank for her. "Cersei Lannister will make a good match", he told me. "You'll need her father on your side." I thought being King meant I could do whatever I wanted. Enough of this! Let's go watch 'em ride. At least I can smell someone else's blood.

author: eddard stark
content: Robert?

author: robert baratheon
content: What? Oh! An inspiring sight for the people, eh? Come! Bow before your King! Bow, you shits!

author: eddard stark
content: Where's Arya

author: sansa stark
content: At her dancing lessons. The Knight of the Flowers.

author: sansa stark
content: Thank you, Ser Loras.

author: sansa stark
content: Don't let Ser Gregor hurt him.

author: eddard stark
content: Hey.

author: sansa stark
content: I can't watch.

author: petyr baelish
content: 100 gold dragons on the Mountain.

author: renly baratheon
content: I'll take that bet.

author: petyr baelish
content: Now what will I buy with 100 gold dragons? A dozen barrels of Dornish wine? Or a girl from the pleasure houses of Lys?

author: renly baratheon
content: Or you could even buy a friend.

author: sansa stark
content: He's going to die.

author: eddard stark
content: Ser Loras rides well.

author: renly baratheon
content: Such a shame, Littlefinger. It would have been so nice for you to have a friend.

author: petyr baelish
content: And tell me, Lord Renly, when will you be having your friend?

author: petyr baelish
content: Loras knew his mare was in heat. Quite crafty, really.

author: sansa stark
content: Ser Loras would never do that! There's no honor in tricks.

author: petyr baelish
content: No honor but quite a bit of gold.

author: robert baratheon
content: Stop this madness in the name of your King!

author: loras tyrell
content: I owe you my life, Ser.

author: sandor clegane
content: I'm no Ser.

author: catelyn stark
content: Remove his hood.

author: marillion
content: On that eve, the captive Imp down-wards from his horse did limp, no more would he preen and primp, in garb of red and gold.

author: tyrion lannister
content: This isn't the Kingsroad. You said we were riding for Winterfell.

author: catelyn stark
content: I did... often and loudly.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Very wise. They'll be out in droves, looking for me in the wrong place. Wordo s probably gotten to my father by now. He'll be offering a handsome reward. Everyone knows a Lannister always pays his debts. Would you be so good as to untie me?

author: catelyn stark
content: And why would I do that?

author: tyrion lannister
content: Why not? Am I going to run? The hill tribes would kill me for my boots. Unless a Shadowcat ate me first.

author: catelyn stark
content: Shadowcats and hill tribes are the least of your concerns.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Ah... the Eastern Road. We're going to The Vale. You're taking me to your sister's to answer for my imagined crimes. Tell me, Lady Stark. When was the last time you saw your sister?

author: catelyn stark
content: Five years ago.

author: tyrion lannister
content: She's changed. She was always a bit touched, but now... you might as well kill me here.

author: catelyn stark
content: I am not a murderer, Lannister.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Neither am I! I had nothing to do with the attempt on your son's life!

author: catelyn stark
content: The dagger found

author: tyrion lannister
content: What sort of imbecile arms an assassin with his own blade?

author: rodrik cassel
content: Should I gag him?

author: tyrion lannister
content: Why? Am I starting to make sense?

author: rodrik cassel
content: My Lady, this way.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Untie me. If I die, what's the point?

author: catelyn stark
content: Rodrik?

author: rodrik cassel
content: I'll be fine, my Lady. There's no need to bloody yourself.

author: bronn
content: Your first? You need a woman. Nothing like a woman after a fight.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Well, I'm willing if she is.

author: maester luwin
content: Bran...

author: bran stark
content: The Iron Islands. Sigil - a Kraken. Words - "We do not sow".

author: maester luwin
content: Lords?

author: bran stark
content: The Greyjoys.

author: theon greyjoy
content: Famed for their skills at archery, navigation and lovemaking.

author: maester luwin
content: And failed rebellions.

author: bran stark
content: Sigil - a stag. - A crowned stag now that Robert's King.

author: maester luwin
content: Good.

author: bran stark
content: Words - "Ours is the fury". Lords - the Baratheons.

author: bran stark
content: The Westerlands - sigil - a lion.

author: maester luwin
content: Hmm...

author: bran stark
content: Words - "A Lannister always pays his debts."

author: maester luwin
content: No. A common saying, but not their official motto.

author: bran stark
content: Lords - the Lannisters.

author: maester luwin
content: We're still on their words.

author: bran stark
content: I don't know them.

author: maester luwin
content: You do know them. Think.

author: bran stark
content: Unbowed, unbent, unbroken".

author: maester luwin
content: That's House Martell.

author: bran stark
content: Righteous in wrath".

author: maester luwin
content: House Hornwood.

author: bran stark
content: Family, duty, honor".

author: maester luwin
content: Those are Tully words... Your mother's. Are we playing a game?

author: bran stark
content: Family, duty, honor"... Is that the right order?

author: maester luwin
content: You know it is.

author: bran stark
content: Family comes first?

author: maester luwin
content: Your mother had to leave Winterfell to protect the family.

author: bran stark
content: How can she protect the family, if she's not with her family?

author: maester luwin
content: Your mother sat by your bed for three weeks while you slept.

author: bran stark
content: And then she left!

author: maester luwin
content: When you were born, I was the one who pulled you from your mother. I placed you in her arms. From that moment until the moment she dies, she will love you. Absolutely. Fiercely.

author: bran stark
content: Why did she leave?

author: maester luwin
content: I still can't tell you, but she will be home soon.

author: bran stark
content: Do you know where she is now? Today?

author: maester luwin
content: No, I don't.

author: bran stark
content: Then how can you promise me she'll be home soon?

author: maester luwin
content: Sometimes I worry you're too smart for your own good.

author: bran stark
content: I'll never shoot another arrow.

author: maester luwin
content: And where is that written?

author: bran stark
content: You need legs to work a bow.

author: maester luwin
content: Hmm... If the saddle Lord Tyrion designed actually works, you could learn to shoot a bow from horseback.

author: bran stark
content: Really?

author: maester luwin
content: Dothraki boys learn when they're four years old. Why shouldn't you?

author: theon greyjoy
content: Shh... Keep it down. You're not supposed to be inside the castle walls.

author: ros
content: I thought you were supposed to be an important person around here.

author: theon greyjoy
content: Important enough for the likes of you.

author: ros
content: You're not the only nobleman in my life, you know.

author: theon greyjoy
content: Who? the Imp? I'd call him half a nobleman.

author: ros
content: Jealous?

author: theon greyjoy
content: Why should I be jealous?

author: theon greyjoy
content: Anyone with a few coppers in his pocket can own you for the night. What's a dwarf like down below? I've always wondered.

author: ros
content: Might surprise you.

author: theon greyjoy
content: Hmm?

author: ros
content: He's good with his fingers too. And his tongue.

author: theon greyjoy
content: Generous tipper. I guess gold is cheap for a Lannister.

author: ros
content: You are jealous.

author: theon greyjoy
content: I'm a Greyjoy. We've been Lords of the Iron Islands for 300 years. There's not a family in Westeros that can look down on us, not even the Lannisters.

author: ros
content: And what about the Starks?

author: theon greyjoy
content: I've been Lord Stark's ward since I was eight years old.

author: ros
content: A “ward”, that's a nice word for it. Your father rebelled against King Robert and if he does it again…

author: theon greyjoy
content: My father fought for the freedom of his people! What did your father do? Fucked a cook and whelped a whore.

author: ros
content: You're a very serious boy.

author: theon greyjoy
content: I'm not a boy.

author: ros
content: Oh, yes you are. A serious boy, with a serious cock.

author: theon greyjoy
content: I don't want to pay for it.

author: ros
content: Then get yourself a wife.

author: arya stark
content: Come on. I'm not gonna hurt you.

author: varys
content: How is your son, my Lord?

author: eddard stark
content: He'll never walk again.

author: varys
content: But his mind is sound?

author: eddard stark
content: So they say.

author: varys
content: A blessing then. I suffered an early mutilation myself. Some doors close forever... others open in the most unexpected places. May I?

author: varys
content: If the wrong ears heard what I'm about to tell you, off comes my head. And who would mourn poor Varys then? North or South, they sing no songs for spiders. But there are things you must know. You are the King's Hand and the King is a fool... your friend, I know, but a fool... and doomed unless you save him.

author: eddard stark
content: I've been in the capital a month. Why have you waited so long to tell me this?

author: varys
content: I didn't trust you.

author: eddard stark
content: So why do you trust me now?

author: varys
content: The Queen is not the only one who has been watching you closely. There are few men of honor in the capital. You are one of them. I would like to believe I am another, strange as that may seem.

author: eddard stark
content: What sort of doom does the King face?

author: varys
content: The same sort as Jon Arryn. The tears of Lys, they call it. A rare and costly thing, as clear and tasteless as water. It leaves no trace.

author: eddard stark
content: Who gave it to him?

author: varys
content: Some dear friend, no doubt. But which one? There were many. Lord Arryn was a kind and trusting man. There was one boy... all he was he owed to Jon Arryn.

author: eddard stark
content: The squire, Ser Hugh?

author: varys
content: Pity what happened to him, just when his life seemed to be going so nicely.

author: eddard stark
content: If Ser Hugh poisoned him, who paid Ser Hugh?

author: varys
content: Someone who could afford it.

author: eddard stark
content: Jon was a man of peace. He was Hand for 17 years -- 17 good years. Why kill him?

author: varys
content: He started asking questions.

author: varys
content: He's found one bastard already. He has the book. The rest will come.

author: illyrio mopatis
content: And when he knows the truth, what will he do?

author: varys
content: The gods alone know. The fools tried to kill his son. What's worse, they botched it. The wolf and the lion will be at each other's throats. We will be at war soon, my friend.

author: illyrio mopatis
content: What good is war now? We're not ready. If one Hand can die, why not a second?

author: varys
content: This Hand is not the other.

author: illyrio mopatis
content: We need time. Khal Drogo will not make his move until his son is born. You know how these savages are.

author: varys
content: Delay," you say. "Move fast, " I reply. This is no longer a game for two players.

author: illyrio mopatis
content: It never was.

author: varys
content: The first to arrive and the last to leave. I admire your industry.

author: petyr baelish
content: You do move quietly.

author: varys
content: We all have our qualities.

author: petyr baelish
content: You look a bit lonely today. You should pay a visit to my brothel this evening. First boy is on the house.

author: varys
content: I think you're mistaking business with pleasure.

author: petyr baelish
content: Am I? All those birds that whisper in your ear, such pretty little things. Trust me, we accommodate all inclinations.

author: varys
content: Oh, I'm sure. Lord Redwyne likes his boys very young, I hear.

author: petyr baelish
content: I'm a purveyor of beauty and discretion, both equally important.

author: varys
content: Though I suppose beauty is a subjective quality, no? Is it true that Ser Marlon of Tumblestone prefers amputees?

author: petyr baelish
content: All desires are valid to a man with a full purse.

author: varys
content: And I heard the most awful rumor about a certain lord with a taste for fresh cadavers. Must be enormously difficult to accommodate that inclination. The logistics alone... to find beautiful corpses before they rot.

author: petyr baelish
content: Strictly speaking, such a thing would not be in accordance with the King's laws.

author: varys
content: Strictly speaking.

author: petyr baelish
content: Tell me. Does someone, somewhere, keep your balls in a little box? I've often wondered.

author: varys
content: Do you know, I have no idea where they are? And we had been so close. But enough about me. How have you been since we last saw each other?

author: petyr baelish
content: Since you last saw me or since I last saw you?

author: varys
content: Now the last time I saw you, you were talking to the Hand of the King.

author: petyr baelish
content: Saw me with your own eyes?

author: varys
content: Eyes I own.

author: petyr baelish
content: Council business. We all have so much to discuss with Ned Stark.

author: varys
content: Everyone's well aware of your enduring fondness for Lord Stark's wife. If the Lannisters were behind the attempt on the Stark boy's life and it was discovered that you helped the Starks come to that conclusion... To think... A simple word to the Queen...

author: petyr baelish
content: One shudders at the thought.

author: varys
content: Oh.

author: petyr baelish
content: But you know something? I do believe that I have seen you even more recently than you have seen me.

author: varys
content: Have you?

author: petyr baelish
content: Yes. Earlier today, I distinctly recall seeing you talking to Lord Stark in his chambers.

author: varys
content: Was that you under the bed?

author: petyr baelish
content: And not long after that when I saw you escorting a certain foreign dignitary... Council business? Of course you would have friends from across The Narrow Sea. You're from there yourself, after all. We're friends, aren't we, Lord Varys? I'd like to think we are. So you can imagine my burden, wondering if the King might question my friendo s sympathies… To stand at a crossroads where turning left means loyalty to a friend, turning right, loyalty to the realm.

author: varys
content: Oh, please.

author: petyr baelish
content: To find myself in a position where a simple word to the King --

author: renly baratheon
content: What are you two conspiring about? Well, whatever it is, you'd best hurry up. My brother is coming.

author: petyr baelish
content: To a small council meeting?

author: varys
content: Disturbing news from far away. Haven't you heard?

author: guard
content: Off with you. No begging.

author: arya stark
content: I'm not a beggar. I live here.

author: guard
content: D'you want a smack on your ear to help you with your hearing?

author: arya stark
content: I want to see my father.

author: guard
content: I want to fuck the Queen, for all the good it does me.

author: guard
content: You want your father, boy? He's lying on the floor of some tavern, getting pissed on by his friends.

author: arya stark
content: My father is Hand of the King! I'm not a boy. I'm Arya Stark of Winterfell and if you lay a hand on me, my father will have both your heads on spikes! Now are you going to let me by or do I need to smack you on the ear to help with your hearing?

author: eddard stark
content: You know I had half my guard out searching for you? You promised me this would stop.

author: arya stark
content: They said they were going to kill you.

author: eddard stark
content: Who did?

author: arya stark
content: I didn't see them, but I think one was fat.

author: eddard stark
content: Oh, Arya.

author: arya stark
content: I'm not lying! They said you found the bastard and the wolves are fighting the lions and the savage... something about the savage.

author: eddard stark
content: Where did you hear this?

author: arya stark
content: In the dungeons, near the dragon skulls.

author: eddard stark
content: What were you doing in the dungeons?

author: arya stark
content: Chasing a cat.

author: jory cassel
content: Pardon, my Lord. There's a Night's Watchman here begging a word. He says it's urgent.

author: eddard stark
content: Your name, friend?

author: yoren
content: Yoren, if it please. This must be your son. He has the look.

author: arya stark
content: I'm a girl!

author: eddard stark
content: Did Benjen send you?

author: yoren
content: No one sent me, my Lord. I'm here to find men for The Wall, see if there's any scum in the dungeons that might be fit for service.

author: eddard stark
content: Ah, we'll find recruits for you.

author: yoren
content: Thank you, my Lord. But that's not why I disturb you now. Your brother, Benjen... his blood runs black, makes him as much my brother as yours. It's for his sake I rode here so hard I damn near killed my horse! There are others riding too. The whole city will know by tomorrow.

author: eddard stark
content: Know what?

author: yoren
content: Best said in private, my Lord.

author: eddard stark
content: Go on. We'll talk more later.

author: eddard stark
content: Jory, take her safely to her room.

author: jory cassel
content: Come along, my Lady. You heard your father.

author: arya stark
content: How many guards does my father have?

author: jory cassel
content: Here in King's Landing? Fifty.

author: arya stark
content: You wouldn't let anyone kill him, would you?

author: jory cassel
content: No fear on that count, little Lady.

author: eddard stark
content: Well?

author: yoren
content: It's about your wife, my Lord. She's taken the Imp.

author: vardis egen
content: You're far from home, Lady Stark.

author: catelyn stark
content: To whom do I speak?

author: vardis egen
content: Ser Vardis Egen, Knight of The Vale. Is Lady Arryn expecting your visit?

author: catelyn stark
content: There was no time to send word.

author: vardis egen
content: May I ask, my Lady, why he is with you?

author: catelyn stark
content: That's why there was no time. He is my prisoner.

author: vardis egen
content: He doesn't look like a prisoner.

author: catelyn stark
content: My sister will decide what he looks like.

author: vardis egen
content: Yes, my Lady. She will at that.

author: tyrion lannister
content: The Eyrie. They say it's impregnable.

author: bronn
content: Give me 10 good men and some climbing spikes... I'll impregnate the bitch.

author: tyrion lannister
content: I like you.

author: steward
content: Lord Stark, your presence has been requested in the small council chamber. A meeting has been called.

author: eddard stark
content: I need to see the King first -- alone.

author: steward
content: The King is at the small council meeting, my Lord. He has summoned you.

author: eddard stark
content: Is it about my wife?

author: steward
content: No, my Lord. I believe it concerns Daenerys Targaryen.

author: robert baratheon
content: The whore is pregnant.

author: eddard stark
content: You're speaking of murdering a child.

author: robert baratheon
content: I warned you this would happen. Back in the North, I warned you, but you didn't care to hear. Well, hear it now. I want 'em dead, mother and child both. And that fool, Viserys as well. Is that plain enough for you? I want them both dead.

author: eddard stark
content: You will dishonor yourself forever if you do this.

author: robert baratheon
content: Honor?! I've got Seven Kingdoms to rule! One King, Seven Kingdoms. Do you think honor keeps them in line? Do you think it's honor that's keeping the peace? It's fear! Fear and blood!

author: eddard stark
content: Then we're no better than the Mad King.

author: robert baratheon
content: Careful, Ned. Careful now.

author: eddard stark
content: You want to assassinate a girl... Because the Spider heard a rumor?

author: varys
content: No rumor, my Lord. The princess is with child.

author: eddard stark
content: Based on whose information?

author: varys
content: Ser Jorah Mormont. He is serving as adviser to the Targaryens.

author: eddard stark
content: Mormont? You bring us the whispers of a traitor half a world away and call it fact?

author: petyr baelish
content: Jorah Mormont's a slaver, not a traitor. Small difference, I know, to an honorable man.

author: eddard stark
content: He broke the law, betrayed his family, fled our land. We commit murder on the word of this man?

author: robert baratheon
content: And if he's right? If she has a son? A Targaryen at the head of a Dothraki army… What then?

author: eddard stark
content: The Narrow Sea still lies between us. I'll fear the Dothraki the day they teach their horses to run on water.

author: robert baratheon
content: Do nothing? That's your wise advice? Do nothing til our enemies are on our shores? You're my council? Counsel! Speak sense to this honorable fool.

author: varys
content: I understand your misgivings, my Lord. Truly, I do. It is a terrible thing we must consider, a vile thing. Yet, we who presume to rule must sometimes do vile things for the good of the realm. Should the gods grant Daenerys a son, the realm will bleed.

author: grand maester pycelle
content: I bear this girl no ill will, but should the Dothraki invade, how many innocents will die? How many towns will burn? Is it not wiser, kinder even, that she should die now so that tens of thousands might live?

author: renly baratheon
content: We should have had them both killed years ago.

author: petyr baelish
content: When you find yourself in bed with an ugly woman, best close your eyes, get it over with. Cut her throat. Be done with it.

author: eddard stark
content: I followed you into war - twice, without doubts, without second thoughts. But I will not follow you now. The Robert I grew up with didn't tremble at the shadow of an unborn child.

author: robert baratheon
content: She dies.

author: eddard stark
content: I will have no part in it.

author: robert baratheon
content: You're the King's Hand, Lord Stark. You'll do as I command or I'll find me a Hand who will.

author: eddard stark
content: And good luck to him. I thought you were a better man.

author: robert baratheon
content: Out! Out, damn you! I'm done with you. Go! Run back to Winterfell! I'll have your head on a spike! I'll put it there myself, you fool! You think you're too good for this? Too proud and honorable? This is a war!

author: eddard stark
content: I'll go ahead with my daughters. Get them ready. Do it yourself. Don't ask anyone for help.

author: jory cassel
content: Right away, my Lord. Lord Baelish is here for you.

author: petyr baelish
content: His Grace went on about you at some length after you took your leave. The word "treason" was mentioned.

author: eddard stark
content: What can I do for you?

author: petyr baelish
content: When do you return to Winterfell?

author: eddard stark
content: Why? What do you care?

author: petyr baelish
content: If you're still here come nightfall, I'll take you to see the last person Jon Arryn spoke with before falling ill. If that sort of thing still interests you.

author: eddard stark
content: I don't have the time.

author: petyr baelish
content: It won't take more than an hour. But as you please.

author: eddard stark
content: Round up all the men we have and station them outside the girls' chambers. Who are your best two swords?

author: jory cassel
content: Heward and Wyl.

author: eddard stark
content: Find them and meet me at the stables.

author: lysa arryn
content: You bring him here without permission? You pollute my home with his presence? Your aunt has done a bad thing, Robin, a very bad thing. You remember her, don't you? Isn't he beautiful? And strong too. Jon knew it. His last words were, "the seed is strong." He wanted everyone to know what a good, strong boy his son would grow up to be. Look at him, the Lord of all the Vale.

author: catelyn stark
content: Lysa, you wrote me about the Lannisters, warning me t-

author: lysa arryn
content: To stay away from them! Not to bring one here!

author: robin arryn
content: Mommy? Is that the bad man?

author: lysa arryn
content: It is.
