content: I help manage his affairs.

author: shae
content: He's an important person.

author: ros
content: So is she. I grew up in the shadow of her father's castle. The day she was born, they rang the bells from sunrise till sunset. We've both done rather well, you and I.

author: shae
content: Yes.

author: ros
content: Given where we started.

author: shae
content: And where is that?

author: ros
content: It's not easy for girls like us to dig our way out. Watch out for her.

author: shae
content: I always do.

author: ros
content: Watch out for her with him.

author: jorah mormont
content: They're growing fast.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Not fast enough. I can't wait that long. I need an army

author: jorah mormont
content: We'll be in Astapor by nightfall. Some say the Unsullied are the greatest soldiers in the world.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: The greatest slave-soldiers in the world. The distinction means a good deal to some people.

author: jorah mormont
content: Do those people have any better ideas about how to put you on the Iron Throne?

author: daenerys targaryen
content: It's too beautiful a day to argue.

author: jorah mormont
content: You're right. Another lovely day on the high seas.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Don't mock them. They're the first Dothraki who have ever been on a ship. They followed me across the poison water. If they'll do it, others will. And with a true khalasar ...

author: jorah mormont
content: The Dothraki follow strength above all, khaleesi. You'll have a true khalasar when you prove yourself strong. And not before.

author: davos
content: Your Grace.

author: stannis baratheon
content: I heard you were dead.

author: davos
content: Not yet.

author: stannis baratheon
content: I had hoped to speak to you alone, Your Grace.

author: stannis baratheon
content: We are alone.

author: davos
content: Your Grace, you are the rightful king. Not only by blood. You're an honorable man, a just man. And there is still a war to fight.

author: stannis baratheon
content: I am fighting.

author: davos
content: By burning prisoners alive?

author: melisandre
content: How would you punish the infidels, Ser Davos?

author: davos
content: I do not judge people for the gods they worship. If I did, I'd have thrown you in the sea before you ever set foot on Dragonstone.

author: melisandre
content: I'm not your enemy.

author: davos
content: You are my enemy.

author: melisandre
content: Was it me you fought on Blackwater Bay? Did I set your ships ablaze? I wasn't there when the wildfire killed our men by the thousands. I could have saved those men. You would have taken the city, Stannis would now sit upon his rightful throne, and you would stand beside him. But I wasn't there because you convinced your king to leave me behind. Do you hear them screaming? All those burning men in the water crying for their mothers, for their gods for help? Until the moment the Blackwater swallowed them.

author: melisandre
content: Don't despair, Ser Davos. What I told your son is true.

author: melisandre
content: Death by fire is the purest death.

author: davos
content: This woman is evil! She's the mother of demons.

author: stannis baratheon
content: Take him to the dungeon and lock him in a cell.

author: davos
content: Your Grace!

author: guard
content: Come on.

author: melisandre
content: You've chosen the darkness, Ser Davos.

author: davos
content: She will destroy us all!

author: melisandre
content: I will pray for you.

author: guard
content: Guard

author: guard
content: Guard #2

author: joffrey lannister
content: Why have we stopped?

author: guard
content: It's Lady Margaery, Your Grace.

author: joffrey lannister
content: What is she doing? Who gave her permission?

author: maid
content: My lady. We should have guards, my lady.

author: margaery tyrell
content: Why?

author: margaery tyrell
content: Pardon me.

author: maid
content: Stop, my lady. You'll ruin your dress.

author: margaery tyrell
content: I have others.

author: guard
content: Would you like to speak with her, Your Grace?

author: joffrey lannister
content: No.

author: child
content: He was a soldier. He went to fight on the walls when the ships came into Blackwater Bay. He never came back.

author: margaery tyrell
content: And your mother?

author: child
content: She died when she had me.

author: margaery tyrell
content: Bad men wanted to come into this city and do terrible things, but your father stopped them.

author: margaery tyrell
content: Whenever you look at this knight, I want you to remember your father.

author: child
content: He wasn't a knight. He was just a soldier.

author: margaery tyrell
content: And what do knights swear to do? Protect the weak and uphold the good. Your father did that. Be proud of him.

author: margaery tyrell
content: Was your father a soldier, too?

author: margaery tyrell
content: You should be proud, too. Under King Joffrey's leadership, your fathers saved the city. They saved us all. From now on, we're going to take care of you. All of you.

author: margaery tyrell
content: Come to me for whatever you need to feed them, clothe them, or house them. Directly to me.

author: margaery tyrell
content: Your Grace.

author: loras
content: Your Grace.

author: joffrey lannister
content: Please, sit. Sit. I do apologize, my lady. Small council meetings. At what point does it become treason to waste the king's time?

author: joffrey lannister
content: That's a lovely gown, my lady.

author: cersei lannister
content: Yes, it suits you perfectly. I imagine you might be rather cold.

author: margaery tyrell
content: The climate is a bit more forgiving back in Highgarden, Your Grace.

author: joffrey lannister
content: Shall I have them bring you a shawl, my lady?

author: margaery tyrell
content: I am touched by your concern, Your Grace. Luckily for us Tyrells, our blood runs quite warm. Doesn't it, Loras?

author: loras
content: Yes.

author: margaery tyrell
content: Loras, isn't the queen's gown magnificent? The fabric, the embroidery, the metalwork. I've never seen anything like it.

author: cersei lannister
content: You might find a bit of armor quite useful once you become queen. Perhaps before. Joffrey tells me you stopped your carriage at Flea Bottom on your way back from the sept this morning.

author: margaery tyrell
content: Yes. I paid a visit to an orphanage the High Septon told me about.

author: loras
content: Margaery does a great deal of work with the poor back in Highgarden.

author: margaery tyrell
content: The lowest among us are no different from the highest if you give them a chance and approach them with an open heart.

author: cersei lannister
content: An open heart is what you'll get in Flea Bottom if you're not careful, my dear. Not long ago, we were attacked by a mob there. We had a full complement of guards that didn't stop them. The king barely escaped with his life.

author: joffrey lannister
content: My mother's always had a penchant for drama. Facts become less and less important to her as she grows older. Our lives were never truly in danger.

author: cersei lannister
content: You're right, of course. But you are your father's son. We can't all have a king's bravery.

author: margaery tyrell
content: Hunger turns men into beasts. I'm glad House Tyrell has been able to help in this regard. They tell me 100 wagons arrive daily now from the Reach. Wheat, barley, apples. We've had a blessed harvest. And, of course, it's our duty to assist the capital in time of need.

author: joffrey lannister
content: Well, as Ser Loras said, Lady Margaery has done this sort of... charitable work before. I'm sure she knows what she's doing.

author: cersei lannister
content: I'm sure she does.

author: missandei
content: The Unsullied have stood here for a day and a night with no food or water.

author: missandei
content: They will stand until they drop.

author: missandei
content: Such is their obedience.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: They may suit my needs. Tell me of their training.

author: missandei
content: The Westrosi woman is pleased with them, but speaks no praise to keep the price down. She wished to know how they are trained.

author: kraznys mo nakloz
content: Tell her what she would know and be quick about it.

author: missandei
content: They begin their training at five. Every day they drill from dawn to dusk until they have mastered the shortsword, the shield, and the three spears. Only one boy in four survives this rigorous training.

author: missandei
content: Their discipline and loyalty are absolute. They fear nothing.

author: jorah mormont
content: Even the bravest men fear death.

author: missandei
content: The knight says even brave men fear death.

author: kraznys mo nakloz
content: Tell the old man he smells of piss.

author: missandei
content: Truly, master?

author: kraznys mo nakloz
content: No, not truly. Are you a girl or a goat to ask such a thing?

author: missandei
content: My master says the Unsullied are not men. Death means nothing to them.

author: kraznys mo nakloz
content: Tell this ignorant whore of a Westerner to open her eyes and watch.

author: missandei
content: He begs you attend to this carefully, Your Grace.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Tell the good master there is no need.

author: kraznys mo nakloz
content: She's worried about their nipples? Doers the dumb bitch know we've cut off their balls?

author: missandei
content: My master points out that men don't need nipples.

author: kraznys mo nakloz
content: Here, I'm done with you.

author: unsullied
content: This one is pleased to have served you.

author: missandei
content: To win his shield, an Unsullied must go to the slave marts with a silver mark, find a newborn, and kill it before its mother's eyes. This way, my master says, we make certain there is no weakness left in them.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: You take a babe from its mother's arms, kill it as she watches, and pay for her pain with a silver coin?

author: missandei
content: She is offended. She asks if you pay a sliver coin to the mother for her dead baby.

author: kraznys mo nakloz
content: What a soft mewling fool this one is.

author: missandei
content: My master would like you to know that the silver is paid to the baby's owner, not the mother.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: How many do you have to sell?

author: missandei
content: Eight thousand.

author: kraznys mo nakloz
content: Tell the Westerosi whore she has until tomorrow.

author: missandei
content: Master Kraznys asks that you please hurry. Many other buyers are interested.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Eight thousand dead babies.

author: jorah mormont
content: The Unsullied are a means to an end.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Once I own them, these men...

author: jorah mormont
content: They're not men. Not anymore.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Once I own an army of slaves, what will I be?

author: jorah mormont
content: Do you think these slaves will have better lives serving Kraznys and men like him or serving you?

author: jorah mormont
content: You'll be fair to them. You won't mutilate them to make a point.

author: jorah mormont
content: You won't order them to murder babies. You'll see they're properly fed and sheltered. A great injustice has been done to them. Closing your eyes will not undo it.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: The warlocks.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: I owe you my life, Ser.

author: barristan
content: The honor is mine, my queen.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: You know this man?

author: jorah mormont
content: I know him as one of the greatest fighters the Seven Kingdoms has ever seen and as the Lord Commander of Robert Baratheon's Kingsguard.

author: barristan
content: King Robert is dead. I have been searching for you, Daenerys Stormborn, to ask your forgiveness. I was sworn to protect your family. I failed them.

author: jon snow
content: Don't think too much, Bran.

author: jon snow
content: Relax your bow arm.

author: eddard stark
content: And which one of you was a marksman at ten?

author: bran stark
content: Father?

author: jojen
content: You can't kill it, you know.

author: bran stark
content: Why not?

author: jojen
content: Because the raven is you.

author: hodor
content: Hodor.

author: bran stark
content: It's all right, Hodor.

author: osha
content: Were you inside the wolf again, little lord?

author: bran stark
content: No, it was the three-eyed raven.

author: osha
content: He's back.

author: bran stark
content: I tried to kill it, but I couldn't. There was a boy.

author: osha
content: I don't want to hear about it.

author: bran stark
content: But you asked.

author: osha
content: We've got plenty of worries. We don't need to pour black magic on top of them.

author: bran stark
content: I didn't ask for black magic dreams.

author: osha
content: I know you didn't, little lord.

author: osha
content: We need to move.

author: bran stark
content: We don't know who might be after us. No one even knows we're alive.

author: osha
content: And who told you that? The three-eyed raven tell you?

author: bran stark
content: No.

author: osha
content: Some good he is, then.

author: osha
content: I don't know what other people know and what they don't. I only know the Wall is a long way off.

author: talisa
content: My mother always told me you Westerosi were a grim lot. Grim, bearded, stinking barbarians that would row across the Narrow Sea and steal us from our beds.

author: robb stark
content: Did you ever think you'd marry one?

author: talisa
content: I never thought I'd marry anyone at all.

author: robb stark
content: Never?

author: talisa
content: Not until I met the king of the grim, bearded, stinking barbarians.

author: roose bolton
content: Pardon me, Your Grace. My queen.

author: talisa
content: Lord Bolton.

author: robb stark
content: Let me guess which one is the good news.

author: roose bolton
content: Word from Riverrun and Winterfell.

author: catelyn stark
content: I hadn't seen him in years. I don't even know how many.

author: robb stark
content: We'll travel to the funeral together. Lord Bolton will garrison here until we return.

author: catelyn stark
content: Will I be wearing manacles when I lay my father to rest?

author: catelyn stark
content: Something else?

author: robb stark
content: By the time Bolton's bastard Ramsay got to Winterfell, the Ironborn were gone. They massacred everyone and put the castle to the torch. And Bran and Rickon have not been found. They may have escaped. Or Theon may have taken them back to the Iron Islands as hostages.

author: catelyn stark
content: Have you received any demands?

author: robb stark
content: No.

author: catelyn stark
content: Have you heard anything from Theon at all?

author: theon greyjoy
content: Where am I? Who are you? What do you want?

author: torturer
content: I want to do this.

author: jaime lannister
content: Do you know how long it's going to take us to get to King's Landing walking through fields and forests?

author: brienne
content: Yes.

author: jaime lannister
content: So how shall we pass the time?

author: brienne
content: By putting one foot in front of the other.

author: jaime lannister
content: It's going to be a very dull walk.

author: brienne
content: I'm here to take you to King's Landing and bring back Lady Stark's daughters in exchange. Dull is fine.

author: jaime lannister
content: You know, it doesn't matter how loyal a servant you are, no one enjoys the company of a humorless mute. Trust me on this. People have been serving me since I was born. You think Lady Stark is going to want a giant towheaded plank following her around for the rest of her life? A week's journey with you and she'll order you to fall on your sword.

author: brienne
content: If Lady Stark is unhappy with any aspect of my service, I'm sure she'll let me know. She's an honest woman.

author: jaime lannister
content: All the good it's done her.

author: jaime lannister
content: How did you come into Lady Stark's service? There's something we can talk about.

author: brienne
content: Not your concern, Kingslayer.

author: jaime lannister
content: It had to be recently. You weren't with her at Winterfell.

author: brienne
content: How would you know?

author: jaime lannister
content: Because I visited Winterfell. I would have noticed your dour head smacking into the archways.

author: brienne
content: Move.

author: jaime lannister
content: Were you pledged to Stannis?

author: brienne
content: Gods, no.

author: jaime lannister
content: Ah, Renly. Really? He wasn't fit to rule over anything more important than a 12-course meal.

author: brienne
content: Shut your mouth.

author: jaime lannister
content: Why? I lived with him at court since he was a boy, don't forget. Could hardly escape the little tulip. Skipping down the corridors in his embroidered silks. I knew him far better than you.

author: brienne
content: I knew him as well as anyone. As a member of his Kingsguard, he trusted me with everything. He would have been a wonderful king.

author: jaime lannister
content: Sounds like you quite fancied him.

author: brienne
content: I did not fancy him.

author: jaime lannister
content: Oh, gods, you did.

author: jaime lannister
content: Did you ever tell him? No, of course not. You weren't Renly's type, I'm afraid.

author: jaime lannister
content: He preferred curly-haired little girls like Loras Tyrell. You're far too much man for him.

author: brienne
content: I'm not interested in foul rumors.

author: jaime lannister
content: Unless they're about me. It's all true about Renly. His proclivities were the worst kept secret at court. It's a shame the throne isn't made out of cocks. They'd have never got him off it.

author: brienne
content: Shut your mouth!

author: jaime lannister
content: I don't blame him. And I don't blame you, either. We don't get to choose who we love.

author: man
content: Where are you headed, then?

author: brienne
content: South. You?

author: man
content: Riverrun. Staying off the kingsroad, are you? They get you no matter where you go. You can't win.

author: jaime lannister
content: No, you really can't.

author: man
content: Looks like you're safe enough, though. Meaning no offense, my lady, but I wouldn't tangle with you. Seven blessings to you.

author: brienne
content: And you.

author: jaime lannister
content: He knows who I am.

author: brienne
content: He doesn't.

author: jaime lannister
content: Maybe you're right. But what if you're not? What if he tells someone?

author: brienne
content: We're not doing it. He's an innocent man.

author: jaime lannister
content: More innocent than Lady Stark's daughters?

author: joffrey lannister
content: Make it tighter here.

author: cersei lannister
content: That's better. It makes you look very strong.

author: joffrey lannister
content: No flowers. I said no flowers. All these are wrong. Bring others.

author: tailor
content: Yes, Your Grace.

author: joffrey lannister
content: Bloody flowers. On the king.

author: cersei lannister
content: Looks like a Tyrell rose. Give it to Margaery for her wedding gown. Should be more than enough fabric.

author: cersei lannister
content: Tell me what you think of her.

author: joffrey lannister
content: Who?

author: cersei lannister
content: Margaery.

author: joffrey lannister
content: She's an ideal match. With the Tyrells beside us, we'll crush the Northerners. Hang their lords, burn their strongholds, sow their fields with salt, and no one will think of rebelling for another century.

author: cersei lannister
content: It is a good match, but what do you think of her? She's beautiful and intelligent.

author: joffrey lannister
content: Yes, she is.

author: cersei lannister
content: Her concern with the well-being of the common people is interesting.

author: joffrey lannister
content: Not to me.

author: cersei lannister
content: I only meant that to go out of your way to endanger yourself.

author: joffrey lannister
content: This is becoming one of the most boring conversations I've ever had.

author: cersei lannister
content: Margaery Tyrell dotes on filthy urchins for a reason. She dresses like a harlot for a reason. She married a traitor and known degenerate like Renly Baratheon for a reason.

author: joffrey lannister
content: She married Renly Baratheon because she was told to. That's what intelligent women do-what they're told.

author: cersei lannister
content: You need to ask yourself

author: joffrey lannister
content: I don't need to do anything.

author: joffrey lannister
content: Better. Much better.

author: shae
content: I still don't believe it.

author: sansa stark
content: He didn't. He didn't want anything. He just takes an interest because he loved my mother.

author: shae
content: Men only want one thing from a pretty girl.

author: sansa stark
content: Littlefinger's not in love with me.

author: shae
content: Love is not the thing he wants.

author: sansa stark
content: He's too old.

author: shae
content: They never see it that way. He didn't ask you to do something for him? Spy on someone or...?

author: sansa stark
content: No.

author: shae
content: If he does ask you for anything or try anything or touch you, I want you to tell me.

author: sansa stark
content: Why? What will you do? I will make him stop.

author: guard
content: Ser Loras Tyrell, my lady.

author: sansa stark
content: Send him in.

author: loras
content: Lady Sansa.

author: sansa stark
content: Ser Loras.

author: loras
content: My sister Margaery invites you to take the air with her and our grandmother, the Lady Olenna, in the gardens. May I escort you to them?

author: loras
content: I believe you grow more beautiful every day, Lady Sansa.

author: sansa stark
content: You are too kind, Ser Loras. You probably don't remember the first time we met. At the Hando s tourney, you gave me your favor. A rose, a red rose.

author: loras
content: Of course I did.

author: margaery tyrell
content: It's more your color. You take it.

author: maid
content: Thank you.

author: margaery tyrell
content: You're such a dear.

author: loras
content: I'll take my leave. Lady Sansa.

author: sansa stark
content: Thank you, Ser Loras.

author: margaery tyrell
content: Come. Lady Sansa, it is my honor to present my grandmother the Lady Olenna of House Tyrell.

author: olenna tyrell
content: Kiss me, child.

author: olenna tyrell
content: It's so good of you to visit me and my foolish flock of hens. We're very sorry for your losses.

author: sansa stark
content: And I was sorry when I heard of Lord Renly's death, Lady Margaery. He was very gallant.

author: olenna tyrell
content: Gallant, yes. And charming and very clean. He knew how to dress and smile and somehow this gave him the notion he was fit to be king.

author: margaery tyrell
content: Renly was brave and gentle, Grandmother. Father liked him and so did Loras.

author: olenna tyrell
content: Loras is young and very good at knocking men off horses with a stick. That does not make him wise. As to your fathead father-

author: margaery tyrell
content: Grandmother! What will Sansa think of us?

author: olenna tyrell
content: She might think we have some wits about us. One of us, at any rate. It was treason. I warned them. Robert has two sons and Renly has an older brother. How could he possibly have any claim to that ugly iron chair? We should have stayed well out of all this if you ask me. But once the cow's been milked, there's no squirting the cream back up her udders. So here we are to see things through. What do you say to that, Sansa? Shall we have some lemon cakes?

author: sansa stark
content: Lemon cake's my favorite.

author: olenna tyrell
content: So we've been told. Are you going to bring the food or do you mean to starve us to death? Here, Sansa, come sit with me. I'm much less boring than these others.

author: olenna tyrell
content: Do you know my son? The Lord of Highgarden?

author: sansa stark
content: I haven't had the pleasure.

author: olenna tyrell
content: No great pleasure, believe me. A ponderous oaf. His father was an oaf as well. My husband, the late Lord Luthor. He managed to ride off a cliff whilst hawking. They say he was looking up at the sky and paying no mind to where his horse was taking him. And now my son is doing the same, only this time he's riding a lion instead of a horse. Now I want you to tell me the truth about this royal boy, this Joffrey.

author: sansa stark
content: I-, I-

author: olenna tyrell
content: You, you. Who else would know better? We've heard some troubling tales. Is there any truth to them? Has this boy mistreated you?

author: olenna tyrell
content: Has he ripped out your tongue?

author: sansa stark
content: Joff-King Joffrey, he-His Grace is very fair and handsome and as brave as a lion

author: olenna tyrell
content: Yes, all Lannisters are lions. And when a Tyrell farts, it smells like a rose. But how kind is he? How clever? Has he a good heart, a gentle hand?

author: margaery tyrell
content: I'm to be his wife. I only want to know what that means.

author: olenna tyrell
content: Bring me some cheese.

author: servant
content: The cheese will be served after the cakes, my lady.

author: olenna tyrell
content: The cheese will be served when I want it served. And I want it served now.

author: olenna tyrell
content: Are you frightened, child? No need for that. We're only women here. Tell us the truth. No harm will come to you.

author: sansa stark
content: My father always told the truth.

author: olenna tyrell
content: Yes, he had that reputation. And they named him traitor and took his head.

author: sansa stark
content: Joffrey. Joffrey did that. He promised he would be merciful and he cut my father's head off. And he said that was mercy. Then he took me up on the walls and made me look at it.

author: olenna tyrell
content: Go on.

author: sansa stark
content: I-I can't. I never meant-my father was a traitor. My brother as well. I have traitor's blood. Please don't make me say anymore.

author: margaery tyrell
content: She's terrified, Grandmother. Just look at her.

author: olenna tyrell
content: Speak freely, child. We would never betray your confidence, I swear it.

author: sansa stark
content: He's a monster.

author: olenna tyrell
content: Ah. That's a pity.

author: sansa stark
content: Please, don't stop the wedding.

author: olenna tyrell
content: Have no fear. The Lord Oaf of Highgarden is determined that Margaery shall be queen. Even so, we thank you for the truth. Ah, here comes my cheese.

author: rickard karstark
content: We're at war. This march is a distraction.

author: robb stark
content: My grandfather's funeral is not a distraction.

author: rickard karstark
content: Are we riding to battle at Riverrun?

author: rickard karstark
content: Then it's a distraction.

author: robb stark
content: My Uncle Edmure has his forces garrisoned there. We need his men.

author: rickard karstark
content: Unless he's been breeding them, he don't have enough to make a difference.

author: robb stark
content: Have you lost faith in our cause?

author: rickard karstark
content: If it's revenge, I still got faith in it.

author: robb stark
content: If you no longer believe-

author: rickard karstark
content: I can believe till it snows in Dorne. Don't change the fact that we've got half the men.

author: robb stark
content: You don't think we can win?

author: rickard karstark
content: May I speak my mind, Your Grace?

author: robb stark
content: Have you not been speaking your mind, Lord Karstark?

author: rickard karstark
content: I think you lost this war the day you married her.

author: talisa
content: Whoa, whoa.

author: man
content: Your Grace.

author: catelyn stark
content: You're afraid of her. And she knows it.

author: talisa
content: I'm not afraid of her. May I help you, Lady Stark?

author: catelyn stark
content: No.

author: talisa
content: I'm sorry, I shouldn't have-

author: catelyn stark
content: You can't help because a mother makes one for her children to protect them. Only a mother can make them.

author: talisa
content: You've made them before?

author: catelyn stark
content: Twice.

author: talisa
content: Did they work?

author: catelyn stark
content: After a fashion. I prayed for my son Bran to survive his fall.

author: catelyn stark
content: Many years before that, one of the boys came down with the pox. Maester Luwin said if he made it through the night, he'd live. But it would be a very long night. So I sat with him all through the darkness. Listened to his ragged little breaths, his coughing, his whimpering.

author: talisa
content: Which boy?

author: catelyn stark
content: Jon Snow. When my husband brought that baby home from the war, I couldn't bear to look at him. I didn't want to see those brown stranger's eyes staring up at me. So I prayed to the gods, take him away. Make him die. He got the pox. And I knew I was the worst woman who ever lived. A murderer. I'd condemned this poor, innocent child to a horrible death all because I was jealous of his mother. A woman he didn't even know. So I prayed to all seven gods, let the boy live. Let him live and I'll love him. I'll be a mother to him. I'll beg my husband to give him a true name, to call him Stark and be done with it, to make him one of us.

author: talisa
content: And he lived.

author: catelyn stark
content: And he lived. And I couldn't keep my promise. And everything that's happened since then all this horror that's come to my family it's all because I couldn't love a motherless child.

author: mance
content: Was it hard for you to kill the Halfhand?

author: jon snow
content: Yes.

author: mance
content: You liked him? I like you, but if you're playing us false, it won't be hard for me to kill you. I've got wildling blood in my veins. These are my people.

author: jon snow
content: I understand.

author: mance
content: Well, how could you understand?

author: jon snow
content: You want to protect your people.

author: mance
content: Do you know what it takes to unite 90 clans, half of whom want to massacre the other half for one insult or another? They speak seven different languages in my army. The Thenns hate the Hornfoots. The Hornfoots hate the ice-river clans. Everyone hates the cave people. So you know how I got moon worshippers and cannibals and giants to march together in the same army?

author: jon snow
content: No.

author: mance
content: I told them we were all going to die if we don't get south. Because that's the truth.

author: tormund
content: Shouldn't be long now.

author: jon snow
content: What's wrong with him?

author: mance
content: He's a warg. He can enter the mind of animals, see through their eyes. He's scouting for us.

author: ygritte
content: What, you've never met a warg?

author: mance
content: Orell.

author: mance
content: Where were you this time?

author: orell
content: The Fist of the First Men.

author: mance
content: What did you see?

author: orell
content: Dead crows.

author: rast
content: What's the matter, Piggy? You crying 'cause you're cold? There's 200 brothers killed by dead men and you're still here whimpering. That seem fair to you? I seen 'em torn to pieces fighting while you was off somewhere hiding in a hole. Why don't you lie down and rest for a while, eh? You know you want to.

author: grenn
content: Hey. Get up, Sam.

author: sam
content: No.

author: grenn
content: Get up.

author: sam
content: I can't.

author: grenn
content: If you stop, you'll die.

author: dolorous edd
content: Course if you don't stop, you'll probably die, too.

author: sam
content: You don't care.

author: dolorous edd
content: Course we care.

author: sam
content: You left me. When the white walkers came, you left me.

author: dolorous edd
content: Aye, we left you. You're fat and you're slow. We didn't want to die.

author: grenn
content: Help me get him up.

author: rast
content: Looks like that piggy is done for.

author: grenn
content: Help us get him up.

author: rast
content: He's slowing us down.

author: grenn
content: Just get him up!

author: rast
content: Why? So the rest of us can die? We'll move faster without him.

author: jeor
content: What is this? Get up, Tarly. Is he all right?

author: grenn
content: Aye, I think so.

author: rast
content: If he can't, we may as well just go without him.

author: jeor
content: That's enough. Tarly, I forbid you to die. Do you hear me?

author: rast
content: Why should the rest of us-

author: jeor
content: Rast, you're responsible for him.

author: rast
content: What am I supposed to do?

author: jeor
content: Make sure he gets back alive. If he doesn't, you don't. Move on!

author: rast
content: I'm not dying for you, Piggy. You hear me?

author: bran stark
content: Where's Rickon and Hodor?

author: osha
content: Looking for food.

author: bran stark
content: What's out there?

author: osha
content: Not another step, boy. Unless you want to drown in your own blood.

author: jojen
content: I'm unarmed.

author: osha
content: That was poor planning.

author: jojen
content: My sister carries the weapons.

author: meera
content: I'm better with them. Drop the spear.

author: meera
content: Drop it.

author: osha
content: If you kill me, that wolf will tear you to bits.

author: jojen
content: You must be SUMMER.

author: jojen
content: I'm Jojen Reed. This is my sister Meera. We've come a long way to find you, Brandon. And we have much farther to go.

author: gendry baratheon
content: I'm just trying to understand.

author: arya stark
content: Would you please shut up about it?

author: gendry baratheon
content: Jaqen H'ghar offered you three kills.

author: arya stark
content: I'm not listening.

author: gendry baratheon
content: But just explain it to me. He offered to kill any three people you wanted. Dead. All you had to do was give him the names. Anyone. You could have picked King Joffrey.

author: arya stark
content: Shut up.

author: gendry baratheon
content: You could have picked Tywin Lannister.

author: arya stark
content: Jaqen got us out of Harrenhal, so why are you complaining?

author: gendry baratheon
content: But you could have ended the war.

author: arya stark
content: Where are we going?

author: gendry baratheon
content: North.

author: arya stark
content: If we were going north, we should have come to the Red Fork River by now.

author: gendry baratheon
content: Maybe we already passed it.

author: arya stark
content: It's a hundred feet wide. How could we have passed it? If we hit the Red Fork, we can follow it west to Riverrun. My mother grew up there. My grandfather, he's a lord. He'll protect us.

author: gendry baratheon
content: Could be a minstrel.

author: thoros
content: A lion still has claws...

author: hot pie
content: A minstrel's got gold sometimes. We could jump him, tie him up, steal his gold, and buy some food.

author: arya stark
content: Shh.

author: thoros
content: And so he spoke, and so he spoke

author: thoros
content: What's lurking behind that wall? A lion? A wolf?

author: anguy
content: Just a dirty little cub, I think.

author: thoros
content: Loose a few more shafts.

author: arya stark
content: Don't.

author: thoros
content: Put the sword down, girl.

author: arya stark
content: You go on down the road. Just keep on singing so we know where you are. Leave us be and I won't kill you.

author: anguy
content: Generous.

author: thoros
content: You're a dangerous person. I like dangerous people. Why are your friends so shy?

author: arya stark
content: What friends?

author: anguy
content: The fat to your left and the lad beside him.

author: thoros
content: Three young ones on the run carrying castle-forged swords. You escape from Harrenhal?

author: arya stark
content: Who are you?

author: thoros
content: Thoros of Myr. And the fellow here with the bow is Anguy.

author: arya stark
content: No, who do you fight for?

author: thoros
content: The Brotherhood without Banners. Now come along. I want to hear how two boys and a very dangerous girl escaped Harrenhal.

author: hot pie
content: I'm not going with them. The Brotherhood? That's who the Mountain and them lot were looking for. They'll bring us back and put rats in us.

author: thoros
content: You've got nothing to fear from us, son. The lords of Westeros want to burn the countryside. We're trying to save it. Now come on. We'll talk some more over brown bread and stew. And then you can go on your way.

author: anguy
content: Here's the thing, fat

author: anguy
content: When I'm done talking, that arrow's falling down on your fat head. So I advise you move, because I'm done talking.

author: anguy
content: Half the country's starving and look at this one.

author: thoros
content: Maybe he's the reason half the country's starving.

author: shae
content: My lion.

author: tyrion lannister
content: We've spoken of this. You cannot come here.

author: shae
content: But you said I should come to you with any problems.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Did anyone see you? No.

author: shae
content: No.

author: tyrion lannister
content: You sure? My father does not make idle threats. Having you killed would be the high point of his week. You have to be absolutely certain.

author: tyrion lannister
content: All right. What is this problem?

author: shae
content: I'm worried about Sansa. When she spoke with Lord Baelish, his friend warned me about him.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Baelish doesn't have friends.

author: shae
content: I don't know her name.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Oh, Ros? The redhead?

author: shae
content: How do you know her?

author: tyrion lannister
content: I try to know as many people as I can. You never know which one you'll need.

author: shae
content: She's a whore.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Yes, well, we shouldn't be judgmental about these things.

author: shae
content: You fucked her.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Oh, please. All right, yes, I fucked her once. Twice.

author: tyrion lannister
content: But since I met you, my lady, I've been with no one else.

author: shae
content: And was she good? Did you like her?

author: tyrion lannister
content: Not as much as I like you, obviously, or she'd be the one torturing me right now. What did she say about Littlefinger?

author: shae
content: That Sansa shouldn't trust him.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Is there an idiot in any village who trusts Littlefinger?

author: shae
content: We have to protect her.

author: tyrion lannister
content: We can't. Now that the Lannisters have discarded her, Sansa will have many suitors. A great beauty with a very old name.

author: shae
content: A great beauty? Oh, a great beauty?

author: tyrion lannister
content: Yes, she is, objectively, very. Her face is quite pleasing-to other men and to women, people in general. But not to me, of course. I only have eyes for you.

author: shae
content: You pervert. You want her? This child?

author: tyrion lannister
content: I don't even want to talk about her.

author: shae
content: But you are.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Only because you're making me.

author: shae
content: I didn't force you to open your mouth and make words come out.

author: tyrion lannister
content: This is cruel and unfair. Cruelly unfair.

author: shae
content: Oh, the cruelty. Shae is so cruel to me.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Hmm, yes.

author: shae
content: Now do you think I'm cruel?

author: tyrion lannister
content: Only if you stop. But you mustn't come here again.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Do you hear me? You've come to a dangerous place full of dangerous people. Dangerous people.

author: guard
content: Lady Tyrell, my king.

author: joffrey lannister
content: Send her in.

author: margaery tyrell
content: You wanted to see me, Your Grace?

author: joffrey lannister
content: I'm leaving on a hunting trip. I just wanted to make sure you had everything you need before I left.

author: margaery tyrell
content: That's very thoughtful, Your Grace. I have everything I could want.

author: joffrey lannister
content: Good. Good. How are you finding life in the capital? It must be quite a change after Renly's camp.

author: margaery tyrell
content: A welcome one. A military encampment is no place for a lady.

author: joffrey lannister
content: And the bedside of a traitor? Is that a place for a lady?

author: margaery tyrell
content: Your Grace, I tried to do my duty as a wife, that is all.

author: joffrey lannister
content: What was your duty to this traitor as you saw it?

author: margaery tyrell
content: The duty of any wife to any husband-to provide him with children.

author: joffrey lannister
content: You failed to do this.

author: margaery tyrell
content: Why? I-I would not speak ill of the dead, Your Grace.

author: joffrey lannister
content: You think one ought to speak kindly of a traitor merely because he's had a sword put through his heart?

author: margaery tyrell
content: No. I do beg your pardon. The subtleties of politics are often lost on me. Renly I don't believe he was interested in the company of women.

author: joffrey lannister
content: What makes you say this?

author: margaery tyrell
content: Whenever I wanted to make a child with him, he-he had so many excuses, so many late-night war councils. He never wanted to try. Except one evening, after he'd had far too much wine to drink, he suggested something-something that sounded very painful and couldn't possibly result in children. Maybe the fault was with me.

author: joffrey lannister
content: No, he was a known degenerate.

author: margaery tyrell
content: It's such a relief to hear you say so, Your Grace.

author: joffrey lannister
content: Mmm. I've considered making his perversion punishable by death.

author: margaery tyrell
content: As is your right. You must do whatever you need to do.

author: margaery tyrell
content: You are the king.

author: joffrey lannister
content: Yes. I am.

author: joffrey lannister
content: Do you like it? I just had it made. Probably one of the finest weapons in the Seven Kingdoms.

author: margaery tyrell
content: It's beautiful. Will you show me how it works?

author: joffrey lannister
content: It's a new design. Much easier to load. There's no crank. You use this lever to draw the string.

author: joffrey lannister
content: The bolt goes here.

author: joffrey lannister
content: And then you just aim and-

author: margaery tyrell
content: Would you take me hunting sometime? Forgive me, Your Grace. I know a hunt is no place for a woman.

author: joffrey lannister
content: It's not unheard of.

author: margaery tyrell
content: My father would never let me before-

author: joffrey lannister
content: You no longer belong to him. Do you want to hold it?

author: margaery tyrell
content: May I? Please.

author: margaery tyrell
content: I imagine it must be so exciting to squeeze your finger here and watch something die over there.

author: joffrey lannister
content: Could you do it? Could you kill something?.

author: margaery tyrell
content: I don't know, Your Grace Do you think I could?

author: joffrey lannister
content: Yes.

author: margaery tyrell
content: Would you like to watch me?

author: theon greyjoy
content: Stop! Stop!

author: torturer
content: Tell us the truth.

author: theon greyjoy
content: About what?

author: theon greyjoy
content: I don't know what you want.

author: torturer
content: I want the truth.

author: theon greyjoy
content: What truth?

author: torturer
content: Why'd you take Winterfell?

author: theon greyjoy
content: I took it to-I took it-

author: torturer
content: Who gave the orders?

author: theon greyjoy
content: No one. I took it on my own.

author: torturer
content: Why?

author: theon greyjoy
content: To take the North while it was vulnerable.

author: torturer
content: What were you going to do once you took it?

author: theon greyjoy
content: Hold it. Rule it.

author: torturer
content: Good. That's very good.

author: theon greyjoy
content: Why did you do that?

author: torturer
content: I told you. Why did you take Winterfell?

author: theon greyjoy
content: I took it to bring glory to my house and my father.

author: theon greyjoy
content: Wait. Wait, wait, wait. I took it because I hated the Starks. I hated them for holding me prisoner. I wanted to hurt them.

author: theon greyjoy
content: What are you doing?

author: theon greyjoy
content: Please.

author: theon greyjoy
content: I'll tell you anything. Just take it off. Please. Please, just take it off.

author: ramsay bolton
content: Your sister sent me.

author: theon greyjoy
content: Yara?

author: ramsay bolton
content: I'll come for you tonight when the castle sleeps.

author: theon greyjoy
content: No, don't go. Please, please. No, please don't leave me. Please, please. Please, please don't go! Please. Please. Don't leave me. Please don't go.

author: osha
content: Rickon, stay with us.

author: bran stark
content: It's all right. The wolves will protect him.

author: jojen
content: You can get inside his head, see through his eyes.

author: bran stark
content: Only when I'm asleep.

author: jojen
content: That's how it begins until you learn to control it. You're a warg.

author: bran stark
content: It's not just wolves. Sometimes in my dreams there's a-

author: jojen
content: A three-eyed raven?

author: bran stark
content: You've seen it?

author: jojen
content: We saw him together. You haven't forgotten?

author: bran stark
content: Does it have anything to do with warging?

author: jojen
content: No, the raven is something different, something deeper. The raven brings the sight.

author: bran stark
content: Seeing things that haven't happened yet?

author: jojen
content: Or things that happened long before you were born or things that are happening right now thousands of miles away.

author: osha
content: What's he telling him?

author: meera
content: Why don't you ask?

author: osha
content: Isn't he ashamed, your brother, needing you to protect him?

author: meera
content: Where's the shame in that?

author: osha
content: Any boy his age who needs his sister to protect him is gonna find himself needing lots of protecting.

author: meera
content: Some people will always need help. That doesn't mean they're not worth helping.

author: bran stark
content: When my father died, I dreamt it.

author: jojen
content: You didn't dream it. You saw it. So did I.

author: bran stark
content: You have the sight, too?

author: jojen
content: When I told my father about your father for the first time in my life, I saw him cry.

author: bran stark
content: Your father is Howland Reed? Yeah.

author: jojen
content: Yeah.

author: bran stark
content: He saved my father's life during the rebellion.

author: jojen
content: Your father told you about the rebellion? Mine never did. But I saw that, too.

author: bran stark
content: What else have you seen?

author: jojen
content: Only one thing that matters-you.

author: man
content: I never liked the skinny ones. Like drinking from a puddle. Not that I'm averse to drinking from a puddle every now and again, you understand.

author: arya stark
content: I don't drink ale.

author: thoros
content: There's no story so good a drink won't make it better.

author: man
content: Yeah!

author: thoros
content: You see? They've all suffered through my bouts of sobriety. It's very tedious for all concerned. Now, how did three children-

author: arya stark
content: We're not children.

author: thoros
content: How did three young persons such as yourselves, untrained in the art of war, escape from Harrenhal?

author: arya stark
content: Gendry's a smith. He was apprenticed in the armory.

author: thoros
content: A smith, eh? Where'd you train?

author: gendry baratheon
content: King's Landing. Tobho Mott's shop.

author: thoros
content: That criminal. He charges twice as much as every other armorer in the city.

author: gendry baratheon
content: That's because he's twice as good.

author: thoros
content: Aha! A smith and a salesman.

author: arya stark
content: Gendry stole us weapons.

author: thoros
content: Ah, fought your way out of Harrenhal, I see.

author: arya stark
content: He knows how to use a sword and so do I.

author: arya stark
content: My brothers taught me.

author: men
content: Ooh!

author: thoros
content: To your brothers!

author: thoros
content: You can finish your meals before you go. It may be awhile before you see another.

author: arya stark
content: You'll free us?

author: thoros
content: I gave you my word.

author: thoros
content: But before you go, allow me to raise a cup to your-

author: anguy
content: Hey, hey.

author: thoros
content: Now that is an uncommonly large person. How does one manage to subdue such an uncommonly large person?

author: anguy
content: One waits for him to drink until he passes out.

author: thoros
content: Poor man. You have my sympathy.

author: thoros
content: Aha, not a man at all. A Hound!

author: thoros
content: So good to see you again, Clegane.

author: sandor clegane
content: Thoros? The fuck you doing here?

author: thoros
content: Drinking and talking too much. Same as ever.

author: thoros
content: A pretty prize, lads.

author: men
content: Yeah!

author: sandor clegane
content: Girl.

author: sandor clegane
content: What in seven hells are you doing with the Stark bitch?

author: jaime lannister
content: It's a tough decision - take the bridge and risk being seen or cross the great water.

author: brienne
content: Silence, Kingslayer.

author: jaime lannister
content: Anyone can see us on the bridge, but cross by water and the current could take us or I could escape down the river.

author: brienne
content: Good luck.

author: jaime lannister
content: It's wonderful to watch you wrestle with these dilemmas. Which will she choose?

author: jaime lannister
content: Gambler at heart. Wouldn't have guessed.

author: brienne
content: Be quick about it.

author: jaime lannister
content: I need to rest.

author: brienne
content: Get up.

author: jaime lannister
content: I have these, you know, on your feet when you walk too far. What do you call them?

author: brienne
content: Get up now.

author: jaime lannister
content: Corns. I never used to get corns. Of course I used to ride everywhere, not march around like a common foot soldier wearing the same shit boots for over a year.

author: jaime lannister
content: This heel is ruined. There's no way-

author: jaime lannister
content: I never understood why some knights felt the need to carry two swords.

author: jaime lannister
content: Ooh. You move well for a great beast of a woman.

author: jaime lannister
content: You shouldn't grimace before you lunge. It gives away the game.

author: jaime lannister
content: Bit of a quandary for you. If you kill me, you fail Lady Stark. But if you don't kill me, I'm going to kill you.

author: jaime lannister
content: You're good. Graceless, but good.

author: jaime lannister
content: See? If you were willing to hurt me, you might have had me there.

author: locke
content: Looks like your woman's getting the better of you, if you can call that a woman.

author: jaime lannister
content: We enjoy a good fight. Gets our juices flowing. The Flayed Man of House Bolton. A bit gruesome for my taste.

author: locke
content: You sure he's the one?

author: man
content: That's him, all right. I saw him fight at the tourney for Ser Willem Frey's wedding.

author: locke
content: Give the man his silver.

author: jaime lannister
content: Let us go and my father will pay you whatever you want.

author: locke
content: Enough to buy me a new head? If the King in the North hears I had the Kingslayer and let him go, he'll be taking it right off. I'd rather he takes yours.

author: edmure
content: If I may, nephew, I encountered a situation with one of my lieutenants at the Stone Mill which may have some bearing-

author: brynden
content: Why don't you shut your mouth about that damned mill? And don't call him "nephew." He is your king.

author: edmure
content: Robb knows I meant him no disr-

author: brynden
content: You're lucky I'm not your king. I wouldn't let you wave your blunders around like a victory flag.

author: edmure
content: My blunder sent Tywin's mad scurrying back to Casterly Rock with his tail between his legs. I think King Robb understands we're not gonna win this war if he's the only one winning any battles. No, there's glory enough to go around.

author: robb stark
content: It's not about glory. Your instructions were to wait for him to come to you.

author: edmure
content: I seized an opportunity.

author: robb stark
content: What value was the mill?

author: edmure
content: The Mountain was garrisoned across the river from it.

author: robb stark
content: Is he there now? Of course not.

author: edmure
content: We took the fight to him. He could not withstand us.

author: robb stark
content: I wanted to draw the Mountain into the west, into our country where we could surround him and kill him. I wanted him to chase us, which he would have done because he is a mad without a strategic thought in his head. I could have that head on a spike by now. Instead, I have a mill.

author: edmure
content: We took hostages. Willem Lannister. Martyn Lannister.

author: robb stark
content: Willem and Martyn Lannister are fourteen years old.

author: brynden
content: Martyn is fifteen, I believe.

author: robb stark
content: Tywin Lannister has my sisters. Have I sued for peace?

author: edmure
content: No.

author: robb stark
content: Do you think he'll sue for peace because we have his father's brother's great-grandsons?

author: robb stark
content: How many men did you lose?

author: edmure
content: But for every man we lost, the Lannisters-

author: robb stark
content: We need our men more than Tywin needs his!

author: edmure
content: I'm sorry. I didn't know.

author: robb stark
content: You would have. Right here today at this gathering if you had been patient.

author: brynden
content: We seem to be running short of patience here.

author: robb stark
content: You know who isn't? Tywin Lannister.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Intimate. Lovely table. Better chairs than the old small council chamber. Conveniently close to your own quarters. I like it.

author: tywin lannister
content: What news of Jaime?

author: tywin lannister
content: Twenty thousand unwashed Northerns have known about his escape for weeks. Collectively, you control more spies and informants than the rest of the world combined. Do you mean to tell me that none of you has any notion of where he is?

author: varys
content: We are trying, my lord.

author: tywin lannister
content: Try harder. What do we have, then?

author: varys
content: Robb Stark and most of his bannermen are in Riverrun for the funeral of his grandfather Lord Hoster Tully. In Stark's absence, Roose Bolton holds Harrenhal, which would seem to make him Lord of Harrenhal, in practice if not in name.

author: tywin lannister
content: Well, let him have it. The name suits our purposes far more than that useless pile of rubble. The Lord of Harrenhal will make a worthy suitor for the widow Arryn.

author: petyr baelish
content: For which I am extremely grateful to you, my lord. Lady Arryn and I have known each other since we were children. She has always been positively predisposed toward me.

author: pycelle
content: A successful courtship would make Lord Baelish acting Lord of the Vale.

author: petyr baelish
content: Titles do seem to breed titles.

author: tywin lannister
content: You'll leave for the Eyrie as soon as possible and bring Lysa Arryn into the fold. Then the young wolf can add his own aunt to the list of people who have taken up arms against him.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Far be it from me to hinder true love, but Lord Baelish's absence would present certain problems. The royal wedding may end up being the most expensive event in living memory. Summer has ended, hard days lie ahead. Not a good time to leave the crown's finances unattended.

author: tywin lannister
content: Fully agreed. Which is why I'm naming you new Master of Coin.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Master of Coin?

author: tywin lannister
content: It would appear to be a position that best suits your talents.

author: tyrion lannister
content: I'm quite good at spending money, but a lifetime of outrageous wealth hasn't taught me much about managing it.

author: cersei lannister
content: I have no doubt you will prove equal to this challenge.

author: pycelle
content: Hear, hear.

author: men
content: He lifted her high in the air. He sniffed and roared and smelled her there. She kicked and wailed, a maid so fair. But he licked the honey from her hair. From there to here, from here to there. All black and brown and covered with hair. He smelled that girl in the summer air. The bear, the bear and the maiden fair.

author: jaime lannister
content: I hope you're pleased. If you had armed me, they never would have taken us.

author: brienne
content: You were armed when we were taken.

author: jaime lannister
content: I was in chains if you recall. Our little match would have ended quite quick if my hands weren't bound.

author: brienne
content: All my life I've been hearing, 'Jaime Lannister, what a brilliant swordsman.' You were slower than I expected. And more predictable.

author: jaime lannister
content: I've been sitting in a muddy pen wrapped in chains for the past year.

author: brienne
content: And I'm a woman. I was still beating you.

author: jaime lannister
content: You were not beating me.

author: brienne
content: Maybe you were as good as people said once. Or maybe people just love to overpraise a famous name.

author: jaime lannister
content: When we make camp tonight, you'll be raped. More than once. None of these fellows have ever been with a noblewoman. You'd be wise not to resist.

author: brienne
content: Would I?

author: jaime lannister
content: They'll knock your teeth out.

author: brienne
content: You think I care about my teeth?

author: jaime lannister
content: No, I don't think you care about your teeth. If you fight them, they will kill you. Do you understand? I'm the prisoner of value, not you. Let them have what they want. What does it matter?

author: brienne
content: What does it matter?

author: jaime lannister
content: Close your eyes. Pretend they're Renly.

author: brienne
content: If you were a woman, you wouldn't resist? You'd let them do what they wanted?

author: jaime lannister
content: If I was a woman, I'd make them kill me. But I'm not, thank the gods.

author: gendry baratheon
content: If I had a proper forge, I could make it good as new.

author: thoros
content: Doesn't have to look pretty. It just has to keep the arrows out of my heart.

author: arya stark
content: Why are you helping him? He takes us prisoner and now he's our friend?

author: thoros
content: You're not our prisoner, little lady.

author: arya stark
content: What am I?

author: thoros
content: Our guest. No one's put any chains on you.

author: arya stark
content: So I can walk away, then?

author: thoros
content: These woods aren't safe for Ned Stark's daughter. You're lucky we found you.

author: sandor clegane
content: You think you're good with that bow, you little twat?

author: anguy
content: Better than anyone you've ever met.

author: sandor clegane
content: A cowardo s weapon. I like to fight up close. I like to see a man's face when I put the steel in him.

author: anguy
content: Why? So you can kiss him?

author: arya stark
content: You remember the last time you were here?

author: sandor clegane
content: Looks like every other shit inn on the road.

author: anguy
content: Now, apologies, but you're one ugly fucker and I'd rather not see you no more.

author: anguy
content: Watch your head. Off we go.

author: driver
content: Walk up!

author: arya stark
content: What are you doing? We're about to leave.

author: hot pie
content: I'm staying.

author: gendry baratheon
content: You're what?

author: hot pie
content: I baked some brown bread for the innkeep and she said she never had better. Told Thoros she's keeping me as a payment for all the free meals she's given him. Anyway, it's not me the Brotherhood wants. My brother ain't no king. I'm not a Stark of "Winterhell".

author: arya stark
content: Winterfell.

author: hot pie
content: You sure?

author: arya stark
content: I'm sure.

author: hot pie
content: Well, I made you something.

author: arya stark
content: What is it?

author: hot pie
content: It's a wolf.

author: gendry baratheon
content: Yes, it is.

author: arya stark
content: That's the tail?

author: hot pie
content: Yeah.

author: gendry baratheon
content: Well, be safe.

author: hot pie
content: Yeah, you, too. Don't get stabbed.

author: gendry baratheon
content: You don't burn your fingers.

author: arya stark
content: Good-bye, Hot Pie.

author: hot pie
content: Good-bye, Arry.

author: man
content: Up you go, little lady.

author: arya stark
content: Hey, Hot Pie. It's really good.

author: catelyn stark
content: A person could almost be forgiven for forgetting we're at war.

author: brynden
content: It often comforts me to think that even in war's darkest days, in most places in the world absolutely nothing is happening.

author: catelyn stark
content: I've missed you, Uncle. Father missed you, too, from the day you left. Maybe he never said it in so many words-

author: brynden
content: Maybe? Your father was a stubborn old ox. I was surprised when he died. Didn't think death had the patience.

author: catelyn stark
content: I'm glad you were with him. I wish to the gods I had been. Did you make peace in the end?

author: brynden
content: After thirty years of fighting, I don't think he remembered what started it. He asked me to stop calling myself Blackfish. He said it was an old joke and it was never funny to begin with. I told him people had been calling me Blackfish for so long, they don't remember my real name.

author: catelyn stark
content: Every time he would leave for the capital or fight in a campaign, I'd see him off. 'Wait for me, little Cat,' he'd say. 'Wait for me and I'll come back to you.' And I would sit at this window every day when the sun came up, waiting. I wonder how many times did Bran or Rickon stare across the moors of Winterfell waiting for me to return. I will never see them again.

author: brynden
content: You mustn't think it. We don't know the truth. They could be in hiding. Robb believes they're alive. And he must go on believing. He's got to remain strong if he's to prevail. And you must remain strong for him.

author: martyn
content: You're Robb Stark's wife.

author: talisa
content: Hold still.

author: martyn
content: Is it true what they say about him?

author: talisa
content: I don't know. What do they say about him?

author: martyn
content: That he can turn into a wolf at night.

author: talisa
content: True.

author: martyn
content: And he eats the flesh of his enemies.

author: talisa
content: True. You're a Lannister, aren't you?

author: martyn
content: Martyn Lannister.

author: talisa
content: Martyn Lannister. You've nothing to fear. My husband doesn't eat children. Unless it's a full moon. It's not a full moon tonight, is it? See? Nothing to fear.

author: mance
content: Always the artists.

author: jon snow
content: It's only horses. No men.

author: ygritte
content: You said there was dead crows.

author: orell
content: There was.

author: mance
content: How many men were here?

author: jon snow
content: About three hundred.

author: mance
content: And you know what those men are now?

author: mance
content: We're all the same to them - meat for their army.

author: jon snow
content: Do you think anyone got away?

author: mance
content: It's not impossible. You don't go far betting against Mormont. But dead or alive, he took a big gamble coming north. And he lost. His best fighting men are dead. And whether he's Lord Commander of the Night's Watch or a blue-eyed corpse, he's a long way from home. Tormund. Climb the Wall. Take Orell and twenty good men. And take this one. He knows Castle Black's defenses better than any of us. And if he's useful, good. If not throw him off the Wall. See if crows can fly.

author: tormund
content: We're finally going to war, old friend?

author: mance
content: Hide near Castle Black. When I give the signal, hit them in the night. They've got a big old wall to hide behind, but it only guards one side.

author: tormund
content: We'll meet again.

author: mance
content: Aye. If you do your job. Ah.

author: orell
content: How will we see your signal?

author: mance
content: Send your eagle above the Wall every night. When it's time, I'm going to light the biggest fire the North has ever seen.

author: sam
content: Ghost?

author: craster
content: What have we here? Frozen crows?

author: jeor
content: We've come a long way.

author: craster
content: Smaller flock than you went north with.

author: jeor
content: We can talk inside.

author: craster
content: Oh, can we?

author: woman
content: They need some water.

author: woman
content: Tether it and I'll be inside.

author: craster
content: Keep your eyes where they belong. They're not for you.

author: karl tanner
content: Bet you feed that pig better than you feed us.

author: craster
content: Aye, pig's got value to me. You should all be kissing my feet for letting you in. I'd have turned you all away if I wasn't a godly man.

author: jeor
content: You are a godly man?

author: craster
content: I am. I got no fear of what's out there. When the white cold comes, your swords and cloaks and bloody fires won't help you. The only ones left will be those who are right with the gods. The real gods.

author: craster
content: Go tell her she can bite down on a rag or she can bite down on my fist. Women. That sow right there gave birth to a litter of eight. Barely a grunt. And she's almost as fat as this one here. Now why don't you dine on him? Carve off what you need as you go. Well, look at him. He's a walking feast.

author: woman
content: Here we are.

author: woman
content: Sharpen these for me, would ya?

author: woman
content: I see the head. Push.

author: woman
content: That's it. You're nearly there. One more push should do it.

author: gilly
content: What is it? What is it?

author: ramsay bolton
content: Keep quiet.

author: ramsay bolton
content: If you can't ride, we don't stand a chance.

author: theon greyjoy
content: I can ride.

author: ramsay bolton
content: You're sure?

author: ramsay bolton
content: Ride east. Follow the rising sun. Your sister's waiting for you.

author: theon greyjoy
content: I'll make you a Lord of the Iron Islands for this.

author: ramsay bolton
content: We're not in the Iron Islands. Go.

author: theon greyjoy
content: Come on. Come on. Come on. Come on. Come on.

author: man
content: Come on back.

author: stannis baratheon
content: You refuse to tell me where you're going?

author: melisandre
content: I don't know yet. The fires will show me.

author: stannis baratheon
content: How long will you be gone?

author: melisandre
content: I don't know.

author: stannis baratheon
content: You're abandoning me.

author: melisandre
content: I will never abandon you. You are the Son of Fire. I am sworn to serve you.

author: stannis baratheon
content: Then serve me.

author: melisandre
content: When I return, you will understand.

author: stannis baratheon
content: My enemies think they've destroyed me. They're laughing at me the way Renly laughed at me. I want Joffrey dead. I want Robb Stark dead. Make me another son.

author: melisandre
content: I cannot.

author: stannis baratheon
content: Why?

author: melisandre
content: You don't have the strength. It would kill you.

author: stannis baratheon
content: I'm not so easily killed. Men have been trying for years.

author: stannis baratheon
content: I want you.

author: melisandre
content: Your fires burn low, my king.

author: melisandre
content: There is another way. A better way.

author: stannis baratheon
content: You told me your magic requires a king's blood.

author: melisandre
content: Yes.

author: stannis baratheon
content: I'm the one true king.

author: melisandre
content: You are. But there are others with your blood in their veins. You will sit on the Iron Throne, but first there must be sacrifices. The Lord of Light demands it.

author: barristan
content: The Walk of Punishment is a warning, Your Grace.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: To whom?

author: barristan
content: To any slave who contemplates doing whatever these slaves did.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Give me your water.

author: jorah mormont
content: Khaleesi, this man has been sentenced to death.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Here, drink.

author: barristan
content: Leave this place, Your Grace. Leave tonight, I beg you.

author: jorah mormont
content: And what is she to do for soldiers?

author: barristan
content: We can find sellswords in Pentos and Myr.

author: jorah mormont
content: Is it 'we' already, Ser Barristan? If you want to sit on the throne your ancestors built, you must win it. That will mean blood on your hands before the thing is done.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: The blood of my enemies, not the blood of innocents.

author: jorah mormont
content: How many wars have you fought in, Ser Barristan?

author: barristan
content: Three.

author: jorah mormont
content: Have you ever seen a war where innocents didn't die by the thousands?

author: jorah mormont
content: I was in King's Landing after the sack, khaleesi. You know what I saw? Butchery. Babies, children, old men. More women raped than you can count. There's a beast in every man and it stirs when you put a sword in his hand. But the Unsullied are not men. They do not rape. They do not put cities to the sword unless they're ordered to do so. If you buy them, the only men they'll kill are those you want dead.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Do you disagree, Ser Barristan?

author: barristan
content: When your brother Rhaegar led his army into battle at the Trident, men died for him because they believed in him, because they loved him, not because they'd been bought at a slaver's auction. I fought beside the last dragon on that day, Your Grace. I bled beside him.

author: jorah mormont
content: Rhaegar fought valiantly, Rhaegar fought nobly, and Rhaegar died.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Did you know him well, Ser Barristan?

author: barristan
content: I did, Your Grace. Finest man I ever met.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: I wish I had known him. But he was not the last dragon.

author: missandei
content: All? Did this one's ears mishear, Your Grace?

author: daenerys targaryen
content: They did not. I want to buy them all.

author: missandei
content: She wants to buy them all.

author: kraznys
content: She can't afford them. The slut thinks that she can flash her tits, and make us give her whatever she wants.

author: missandei
content: There are eight thousand Unsullied in Astapor. Is this what you mean by all?

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Yes. eight thousand. And the ones still in training as well.

author: greizhen
content: If they fail on the battlefield, they will shame Astapor.

author: missandei
content: Master Greizhen says they cannot sell half-trained boys. If they fail on the battlefield, they will bring shame upon all of Astapor.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: I will have them all or take none. Many will fall in battle. I'll need the boys to pick up the swords they drop.

author: kraznys
content: The slut cannot pay for all of this.

author: missandei
content: Master Kraznys says you cannot afford this.

author: kraznys
content: Her ship will buy her a hundred Unsullied, no more.

author: missandei
content: Your ship will buy you Because Master Kraznys is generous.

author: kraznys
content: And this is because I like the curve of her ass.

author: missandei
content: The gold you have left is worth ten.

author: kraznys
content: What is left will buy her ten. I will give her twenty if it stops her ignorant whimpering.

author: missandei
content: But good Master Kraznys will give you twenty.

author: kraznys
content: Her Dothraki smell of shit but will be useful as pig feed.

author: missandei
content: The Dothraki you have with you-

author: kraznys
content: I will give her three for those.

author: missandei
content: The Dothraki you have are not worth what they cost to feed, but Master Kraznys will give you three Unsullied for all of them.

author: kraznys
content: So, ask this beggar queen how will she pay for the remaining 7,877?

author: missandei
content: Master Kraznys asks how you propose to pay for the remaining 7,877 unsullied.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: I have dragons. I'll give you one.

author: barristan
content: You will win the throne with dragons, not slaves, Your Grace.

author: jorah mormont
content: Khaleesi, please.

author: kraznys
content: Three dragons.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: One.

author: kraznys
content: Two.

author: missandei
content: They want the biggest one.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Done.

author: kraznys
content: Done.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: I'll take you as well, now. You'll be Master Kraznys' gift to me. A token of a bargain well struck.

author: missandei
content: She asks that you give me to her, as a present. She asks that you do this now.

author: jorah mormont
content: Khaleesi, a dragon is worth more than any army.

author: barristan
content: Aegon Targaryen proved that.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: You're both here to advise me. I value your advice, but if you ever question me in front of strangers again, you'll be advising someone else. Is that understood?

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Do you have a name?

author: missandei
content: This one's name is Missandei, Your Grace.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Do you have a family? A mother and a father you'd return to if you had the choice?

author: missandei
content: No, Your Grace. No family living.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: You belong to me now. It is your duty to tell me the truth.

author: missandei
content: Yes, Your Grace. Lying is a great offense. Many of those on the Walk of Punishment were taken there for less.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: I offered water to one of the slaves dying on the Walk of Punishment. Do you know what he said to me? 'Let me die.'

author: missandei
content: There are no masters in the grave, Your Grace.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Is it true what Master Kraznys told me about the Unsullied? About their obedience?

author: missandei
content: All questions have been taken from them. They obey, that is all. Once they are yours, they are yours. They will fall on their swords if you command it.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: And what about you? You know that I'm taking you to war. You may go hungry. You may fall sick. You may be killed.

author: missandei
content: Valar morghulis.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Yes, all men must die. But we are not men.

author: tyrion lannister
content: A surprising place to keep the royal ledgers.

author: petyr baelish
content: I'm surprised you're surprised. This is the safest place in the city.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Not for bastards.

author: ros
content: That's all of them, my lord.

author: petyr baelish
content: Thank you, my dear.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Pod. Pod. Take them outside. I'll be there in a moment.

author: podrick
content: Yes, my lord.

author: petyr baelish
content: I hear you owe that boy a significant debt.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Only my life. Not all that significant, I'm afraid.

author: petyr baelish
content: You should have him knighted.

author: tyrion lannister
content: If only the Master of Coin had such power.

author: petyr baelish
content: If only. I owe you a significant debt. Our redheaded friend. You secured her release when the queen detained her.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Oh, that. Of course. A simple misunderstanding.

author: petyr baelish
content: Apparently, Her Grace believed that you two had some sort of special relationship.

author: tyrion lannister
content: We don't. I did fuck her once.

author: petyr baelish
content: I know.

author: tyrion lannister
content: But we don't.

author: petyr baelish
content: I know. But how would the queen get that idea?

author: tyrion lannister
content: Why don't you ask her? Any advice for me on my new position?

author: petyr baelish
content: Keep a low profile.

author: tyrion lannister
content: If I had a gold dragon for every time I heard that joke, I'd be richer than you are.

author: petyr baelish
content: Well, you are richer than I am.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Good point.

author: petyr baelish
content: They're only numbers. Numbers on paper. Once you understand that, it's easy to make them behave. Trivial even. You want a real challenge? Try whores.

author: tyrion lannister
content: I've tried quite a few. Well, lots of work to do. Enjoy the Eyrie.

author: bronn
content: Come on, I'm here later. Come on.

author: bronn
content: Tonight, then. Looks like dull reading.

author: tyrion lannister
content: You think all reading is dull reading.

author: bronn
content: It's an opinion I share with some of the finest men I know.

author: tyrion lannister
content: The secret history of the Seven Kingdoms is written in these pages.

author: bronn
content: Unless Lord Twatbeard made up a bunch of numbers to hide what he's really up to.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Unless he made it all up, yes. Podrick, do keep up.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Podrick.

author: podrick
content: Yes, my lord?

author: tyrion lannister
content: After a long consultation with my colleague Ser Bronn, I finally found a suitable reward for the services you've provided over and above what might be considered reasonable. Tell me, Pod, have you ever been with a woman?

author: podrick
content: No, my lord.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Wonderful. Genna specializes in first-timers.

author: bronn
content: She's not bad with second-timers, either.

author: podrick
content: Uh, my lord

author: tyrion lannister
content: A fair enough repayment for putting your spear through my would-be killer's face, wouldn't you say?

author: tyrion lannister
content: Now, as it happens, Marei is quite the spear handler herself. She's here to thank you for staying by my side as the battle raged all around me.

author: marei
content: He's handsome. You didn't tell me he was handsome.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Kayla is famous from here to Volantis in certain circles. One of four women in the world who can perform a proper Meereenese Knot.

author: podrick
content: My lord, I don't even

author: tyrion lannister
content: She's here to thank you for being a thoroughly respectful fellow who's never once failed to address me as 'my lord.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Be back in time for my supper.

author: bronn
content: Pace yourself, lad.

author: tyrion lannister
content: For years I've heard that Littlefinger is a magician. Whenever the crown needs money, he rubs his hands together and, poof, mountains of gold.

author: bronn
