content: It feels proportionate.

author: tywin lannister
content: Proportionate to what?

author: olenna tyrell
content: The expected extravagance.

author: tywin lannister
content: People who spend their money on this sort of nonsense tend not to have it for long.

author: olenna tyrell
content: You ought to try enjoying something before you die. You might find it suits you.

author: olenna tyrell
content: Not now, Mace. Lord Tywin and I are speaking.

author: olenna tyrell
content: Anyway, I don't know what you're complaining about. I'm paying my share.

author: tywin lannister
content: Shall we stick golden roses in half the meat pies to commemorate your generosity?

author: olenna tyrell
content: No, your heartfelt thank you is its own reward. I would imagine I'd be hearing it again before long. Wars are rather expensive. "The Iron Bank will have it's due." How they love to remind everyone. Almost as much as you Lannisters with your debts.

author: tywin lannister
content: I'm not worried about the Iron Bank.

author: olenna tyrell
content: We both know you're smarter than that. Come, Tywin, let us celebrate young love.

author: bronn
content: All taken care of.

author: tyrion lannister
content: You saw her board the ship?

author: bronn
content: Aye, she's on it.

author: tyrion lannister
content: You saw the ship sail away?

author: bronn
content: No one knows she's there but you, me, and Varys.

author: tyrion lannister
content: How do you know?

author: bronn
content: Because if someone follows me without an invitation, I'm the last person they ever follow.

author: tyrion lannister
content: There's someone following you?

author: bronn
content: She's gone. I know you don't want to believe it, but she is. Now, go drink till it feels like you did the right thing.

author: oberyn martell
content: Hello.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Hello.

author: oberyn martell
content: Not you.

author: olenna tyrell
content: You look exquisite, child. The wind has been at you, though. I haven't had the opportunity to tell you how sorry I was to hear about your brother. War is war, but killing a man at a wedding, horrid. What sort of monster would do such a thing? As if men need more reasons to fear marriage.

author: tyrion lannister
content: My lady. My lady.

author: olenna tyrell
content: Lord Tyrion, you see? Not as bad as all that. Perhaps if your pauper husband were to sell his mule and his last pair of shoes, he might be able to afford to bring you to Highgarden for a visit. Now that peace has come and all is right with the world, it would do you good to see some of it. You must excuse me. It's time I ate some of this food I paid for.

author: musician
content: A coat of gold / Or a coat of red / A lion still has claws And mine, my lord...

author: joffrey lannister
content: Very good. Very good. Off you go.

author: margaery tyrell
content: My love, why don't we make the announcement?

author: joffrey lannister
content: Everyone. The queen would like to say a few words.

author: margaery tyrell
content: We are so fortunate to enjoy this marvelous food and drink. Not all among us are so lucky. To thank the gods for bringing the recent war to a just end, King Joffrey has decreed that the leftovers from our feast be given to the poorest in his city.

author: cersei lannister
content: You're an example to us all.

author: loras
content: Ser Jaime, I'm very sorry.

author: jaime lannister
content: Ser Loras, it's quite all right. Your sister looks very beautiful.

author: loras
content: As does yours.

author: jaime lannister
content: So, looking forward to your wedding?

author: loras
content: Yes, very much.

author: jaime lannister
content: Our fathers are both rather keen on the prospect.

author: loras
content: They certainly are.

author: jaime lannister
content: Perhaps they should get married. If you were to marry Cersei, she'd murder you in your sleep. If you somehow managed to put a child in her first, she'd murder him, too, long before he drew his first breath. Luckily for you, none of this will happen because you'll never marry her.

author: loras
content: And neither will you.

author: brienne
content: Your Grace. My king. My queen.

author: margaery tyrell
content: Lady Brienne. So good of you to come.

author: brienne
content: I'm no lady, Your Grace.

author: cersei lannister
content: Did you just bow?

author: brienne
content: Apologies, Your Grace. I never did master the curtsy.

author: joffrey lannister
content: You're the one who put a sword through Renly Baratheon.

author: margaery tyrell
content: That's not true, my love. Brienne had nothing to do with it.

author: joffrey lannister
content: A shame. I'd knight the man that put an end to that deviant's life.

author: brienne
content: I just wanted to congratulate you both and wish you good fortune. The country has been at war too long. I hope your reign is long and peaceful.

author: joffrey lannister
content: Yes, yes.

author: margaery tyrell
content: Thank you. I hope we see more of you.

author: cersei lannister
content: Lady Brienne. You're Lord Selwyn Tarth's daughter. That makes you a lady whether you want to be or not.

author: brienne
content: As you say, Your Grace.

author: cersei lannister
content: I owe you my gratitude. You returned my brother safely to King's Landing.

author: brienne
content: In truth, he rescued me, Your Grace. More than once.

author: cersei lannister
content: Did he? Haven't heard that story before.

author: brienne
content: Not such a fascinating story, I'm afraid.

author: cersei lannister
content: I'm sure you have many fascinating stories. Sworn to Renly Baratheon. Sworn to Catelyn Stark. And now my brother. Must be exciting to flit from one camp to the next serving whichever lord or lady you fancy.

author: brienne
content: I don't serve your brother, Your Grace.

author: cersei lannister
content: But you love him.

author: brienne
content: Your Grace.

author: pycelle
content: No, no, come to my chambers and I will examine you personally.

author: cersei lannister
content: She'll do no such thing.

author: pycelle
content: Oh, Your Grace. Yes, well, this young lady sought my advice...

author: cersei lannister
content: You should see Qyburn. He's quite good.

author: maid
content: Your Grace.

author: pycelle
content: Qyburn? Deplorable man. Brought shame on the Citadel with his repugnant experiments.

author: cersei lannister
content: More repugnant than your gnarled fingers on that girl's thighs?

author: pycelle
content: Your Grace, I am a man of learning.

author: cersei lannister
content: My little brother had you sent to the Black Cells when you annoyed him. What do you think I could do to you if you annoyed me?

author: pycelle
content: I never meant to annoy anyone.

author: cersei lannister
content: But you are. You annoy me right now. Every breath you draw in my presence annoys me. So here's what I want you to do. I want you to leave my presence. Leave this wedding right now. Go to the kitchens and instruct them that all the leftovers from the feast will be brought to the kennels.

author: pycelle
content: Your Grace, Queen Margaery-

author: cersei lannister
content: The queen is telling you the leftovers will feed the dogs or you will.

author: joffrey lannister
content: A gold dragon to whoever knocks my fool's hat off.

author: tywin lannister
content: You're in rather a good mood.

author: cersei lannister
content: I suppose I am.

author: tywin lannister
content: I won't ask why.

author: cersei lannister
content: Small pleasures.

author: oberyn martell
content: Your Grace. Lord Tywin.

author: tywin lannister
content: Prince Oberyn.

author: oberyn martell
content: I don't believe you have met Ellaria. This is the Lord Hand Tywin Lannister and Cersei Lannister, the Queen Regent. I suppose it is former Queen Regent now. Lord Hand and Lady Cersei, Ellaria Sand.

author: ellaria
content: My lord. My lady.

author: tywin lannister
content: Charmed.

author: cersei lannister
content: Can't say I've ever met a Sand before.

author: ellaria
content: We are everywhere in Dorne. I have 10,000 brothers and sisters.

author: oberyn martell
content: Bastards are born of passion, aren't they? We don't despise them in Dorne.

author: cersei lannister
content: No? How tolerant of you.

author: oberyn martell
content: I expect it is a relief, Lady Cersei, giving up your regal responsibilities. Wearing the crown for so many years must have left your neck a bit crooked.

author: cersei lannister
content: I suppose you'll never know, Prince Oberyn. It's a shame your older brother couldn't attend the wedding.

author: tywin lannister
content: Please give him our regards. With any luck, the gout will abate with time and he will be able to walk again.

author: oberyn martell
content: They call it the rich man's disease. A wonder you don't have it.

author: tywin lannister
content: Noblemen in my part of the country don't enjoy the same lifestyle as our counterparts in Dorne.

author: oberyn martell
content: People everywhere have their differences. In some places, the highborn frown upon those of low birth. In other places, the rape and murder of women and children is considered distasteful. What a fortunate thing for you, former Queen Regent, that your daughter Myrcella has been sent to live in the latter sort of place.

author: joffrey lannister
content: Everyone, silence! Clear the floor. There's been too much amusement here today. A royal wedding is not an amusement. A royal wedding is history. The time has come for all of us to contemplate our history. My lords... my ladies...

author: joffrey lannister
content: I give you. King Joffrey... Renly, Stannis, Robb Stark, Balon Greyjoy. The War of the Five Kings.

author: renly dwarf
content: I'm the rightful king.

author: robb dwarf
content: King in the North!

author: joffrey dwarf
content: Yes!

author: balon dwarf
content: Traitor. You're a traitor.

author: joffrey dwarf
content: For the Seven Kingdoms!

author: joffrey dwarf
content: Let the war begin.

author: stannis dwarf
content: Renly, you're no king.

author: balon dwarf
content: Away, degenerate. Away. Away.

author: renly dwarf
content: Ooh, careful.

author: stannis dwarf
content: Go on.

author: renly dwarf
content: I want you to be my prince. Stannis!

author: balon dwarf
content: Who's got the gold now, Stark?

author: robb dwarf
content: I am the rightful king.

author: balon dwarf
content: Challenge me, ruffian.

author: robb dwarf
content: Take that.

author: balon dwarf
content: I'm drowning. I'm drowning.

author: robb dwarf
content: I am the King in the North!

author: stannis dwarf
content: Not wildfire!

author: tyrion lannister
content: Pay each of them 20 gold when this is done.

author: podrick
content: Yes, my lord.

author: tyrion lannister
content: We'll have to find another way to thank the king.

author: joffrey dwarf
content: Charge!

author: joffrey dwarf
content: Ready, again.

author: robb dwarf
content: I am the King in the North! - Charge!

author: joffrey dwarf
content: Charge! Yes!

author: joffrey dwarf
content: Your head!

author: joffrey dwarf
content: Fine gentlemen.

author: joffrey lannister
content: Well fought. Well fought. Here you are. Champion's purse. Though you're not the champion yet, are you? A true champion defeats all the challengers. Surely there are others out there who still dare to challenge my reign. Uncle. How about you? I'm sure they have a spare costume.

author: tyrion lannister
content: One taste of combat was enough for me, Your Grace. I would like to keep what remains of my face. I think you should fight him. This was but a poor imitation of your own bravery on the field of battle. I speak as a firsthand witness. Climb down from the high table with your new Valyrian sword and show everyone how a true king wins his throne. Be careful, though. This one is clearly mad with lust. It would be a tragedy for the king to lose his virtue hours before his wedding night.

author: tyrion lannister
content: A fine vintage. Shame that it spilled.

author: joffrey lannister
content: It did not spill.

author: margaery tyrell
content: My love, come back to me. It's time for my father's toast.

author: joffrey lannister
content: Well, how does he expect me to toast without wine? Uncle, you can be my cup-bearer seeing as you're too cowardly to fight.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Your Grace does me a great honor.

author: joffrey lannister
content: It's not meant as an honor.

author: joffrey lannister
content: Bring me my goblet.

author: joffrey lannister
content: What good is an empty cup? Fill it.

author: joffrey lannister
content: Kneel. Kneel before your king.

author: joffrey lannister
content: Kneel. I said... kneel!

author: margaery tyrell
content: Look, the pie.

author: joffrey lannister
content: My queen.

author: margaery tyrell
content: Wonderful. Wonderful. My hero.

author: sansa stark
content: Can we leave now?

author: tyrion lannister
content: Let's find out.

author: joffrey lannister
content: Uncle. Where are you going? You're my cup-bearer, remember?

author: tyrion lannister
content: I thought I might change out of these wet clothes, Your Grace.

author: joffrey lannister
content: No, no, no. No, you're perfect the way you are. Serve me my wine.

author: joffrey lannister
content: Well, hurry up. This pie is dry.

author: joffrey lannister
content: Mm, good. Needs washing down.

author: tyrion lannister
content: If it please Your Grace, Lady Sansa is very tired.

author: joffrey lannister
content: No. No, you'll wait here... un...

author: tyrion lannister
content: Your Grace?

author: joffrey lannister
content: It's nothing.

author: margaery tyrell
content: He's choking!

author: olenna tyrell
content: Help the poor boy.

author: olenna tyrell
content: Idiots, help your king.

author: jaime lannister
content: Move away!

author: jaime lannister
content: Joffrey! Joffrey!

author: cersei lannister
content: Help him! Someone help him!

author: cersei lannister
content: Joffrey!

author: ser dontos
content: Come with me now.

author: cersei lannister
content: Joffrey! Joffrey!

author: ser dontos
content: If you want to live, we have to leave.

author: cersei lannister
content: Don't touch him!

author: cersei lannister
content: Joffrey. Please, Joffrey. Joffrey, what is it? Help him!

author: cersei lannister
content: My son.

author: man
content: He's gone. Our king is gone.

author: cersei lannister
content: He did this. He poisoned my son, your king. Take him. Take him! Take him! Take him!

author: cersei lannister
content: You did this. You did this!

author: ser dontos
content: We have to leave.

author: cersei lannister
content: Take him! Take him!

author: cersei lannister
content: Where is his wife? Where's Sansa?

author: tywin lannister
content: Find her. Bar the gates of the city. Seize every ship in the harbor.

author: cersei lannister
content: Where is she?!

author: tywin lannister
content: No one leaves the capital! No one!

author: ser dontos
content: Get in.

author: sansa stark
content: Where are we going?

author: ser dontos
content: Somewhere safe.

author: ser dontos
content: Up you go, my lady. You'll be fine. You're stronger than you know.

author: sansa stark
content: Lord Baelish?

author: petyr baelish
content: Petyr... Are you hurt, my lady?

author: petyr baelish
content: Good. Good. I'm sure you've had quite a fright. Rest easy. The worst is past. Ser Dontos shouts up from his boat.

author: ser dontos
content: Lord Baelish. I promised I'd get her to you safely.

author: petyr baelish
content: Softly, my friend... Voices carry over water.

author: ser dontos
content: I should get back before someone thinks to look for me. LITTLEFINGER First you'll want your pay. 10,000 was it?

author: ser dontos
content: Wait!

author: petyr baelish
content: Shh. You don't want the queen to hear, do you? 1,000 gold cloaks are searching for you. And if they found you, how do you think they would punish the girl who murdered the king?

author: sansa stark
content: I didn't murder anyone.

author: petyr baelish
content: I know. I know. But you must admit it looks suspicious. The king who executed your father, who tormented you for years, and you fled the scene of his murder.

author: sansa stark
content: Why did you kill him?

author: petyr baelish
content: Because he was a drunk and a fool and I don't trust drunk fools.

author: sansa stark
content: He saved me.

author: petyr baelish
content: Saved you? My lady, he followed my orders. Every one of them. And he did it all for gold. Money buys a man's silence for a time. A bolt in the heart buys it forever.

author: sansa stark
content: He was helping me because I saved his life.

author: petyr baelish
content: Yes, and he gave you a priceless necklace that once belonged to his grandmother. The last legacy of House Hollard.

author: petyr baelish
content: I had it made a few weeks ago. What did I once tell you about the capital?

author: sansa stark
content: We're all liars here.

author: petyr baelish
content: Come, my lady. I know you've had a difficult day. But you're safe now. I promise you that. You're safe with me and sailing home.

author: margaery tyrell
content: So am I the queen?

author: olenna tyrell
content: More than you were with Renly. Less than you would have been if Joffrey had done you the courtesy of consummating the marriage before dying. In any case, this would not be an opportune moment to press the issue.

author: margaery tyrell
content: Clawing at his own throat, looking to his mother to make stop... it was horrible.

author: olenna tyrell
content: The world is overflowing with horrible things. But they're all a tray of cakes next to death. They brought me your grandfather's body when he died, you know? Made me look at it.

author: margaery tyrell
content: What was it like?

author: olenna tyrell
content: They took me to the Great Hall and there he was. The man I'd married and suffered to father my children. A great doughy lump I'd sat next to at endless dinners and tedious gatherings. There he was... lying on a table.

author: margaery tyrell
content: One of my husbands preferred the company of men and was stabbed through the heart. Another was happiest torturing animals and was poisoned at our wedding feast... I must be cursed.

author: olenna tyrell
content: Nonsense. Your circumstances have improved markedly. You may not have enjoyed watching him die, but you enjoyed it more than you would have enjoyed being married to him, I can promise you that.

author: margaery tyrell
content: But I would have been the queen.

author: olenna tyrell
content: Our alliance with the Lannisters remains every bit as necessary to them as it is unpleasant for us. You did wonderful work on Joffrey. The next one should be easier.

author: tywin lannister
content: Your brother is dead. Do you know what that means?

author: tywin lannister
content: I'm not trying to trick you.

author: tommen lannister
content: It means I'll become king.

author: tywin lannister
content: Yes, you will become king. What kind of king do you think you'll be?

author: tommen lannister
content: A good king?

author: tywin lannister
content: Mm, I think so as well. You've got the right temperament for it. But what makes a good king? Hmm? What is a good king's single most important quality?

author: cersei lannister
content: This is hardly the place or the time.

author: tommen lannister
content: Holiness?

author: tywin lannister
content: Hmm. Baelor the Blessed was holy. And pious. He built this sept. He also named a six-year-old boy high septon because he thought the boy could work miracles. He ended up fasting himself into an early grave because food was of this world and this world was sinful.

author: tommen lannister
content: Justice.

author: tywin lannister
content: Yeah. A good king must be just. Orys I was just. Everyone applauded his reforms. Nobles and commoners alike. But he wasn't just for long. He was murdered in his sleep after less than a year by his own brother. Was that truly just of him? To abandon his subjects to an evil that he was too gullible to recognize?

author: tommen lannister
content: No.

author: tywin lannister
content: No.

author: tommen lannister
content: What about strength?

author: tywin lannister
content: Yes. Strength. King Robert was strong. He won the rebellion and crushed the Targaryen dynasty. And he attended three small council meetings in 17 years. He spent his time whoring and hunting and drinking until the last two killed him. So, we have a man who starves himself to death, a man who lets his own brother murder him, and a man who thinks that winning and ruling are the same thing. What do they all lack?

author: tommen lannister
content: Wisdom.

author: tywin lannister
content: Yes!

author: tommen lannister
content: Wisdom is what makes a good king.

author: tywin lannister
content: Yes. But what is wisdom? Hmm? A house with great wealth and fertile lands asks you for your protection against another house with a strong Navy that could one day oppose you. How do you know which choice is wise and which isn't? You've any experience of treasuries and granaries or shipyards and soldiers?

author: tywin lannister
content: No. Of course not. A wise king knows what he knows and what he doesn't. You're young. A wise young king listens to his counselors and heeds their advice until he comes of age. And the wisest kings continue to listen to them long afterwards... Your brother was not a wise king. Your brother was not a good king. If he had been, perhaps he'd still be alive. Now, as the king, you will have to marry. Do you understand why?

author: tommen lannister
content: A king needs a queen.

author: tywin lannister
content: Yes, but why? To further the family line. Do you know how that happens?

author: tommen lannister
content: Yes.

author: tywin lannister
content: Yes, but has anyone explained the details to you?

author: tommen lannister
content: I don't think so. It's all relatively straightforward.

author: jaime lannister
content: How are you?

author: tommen lannister
content: I'm all right.

author: jaime lannister
content: You are. You will be. I'll see to that.

author: jaime lannister
content: Please give the queen a moment alone with her son.

author: septon
content: Yes, my lord. All of you.

author: cersei lannister
content: It was Tyrion. He killed him. He told me he would. "A day will come when you think you are safe and happy and your joy will turn to ashes in your mouth." That's what he said to me. You saw it. You saw Joff point at him just before he...

author: jaime lannister
content: I don't know what I saw.

author: cersei lannister
content: Avenge him. Avenge our son. Kill Tyrion.

author: jaime lannister
content: Tyrion's my brother. Our brother. There'll be a trial. We'll get to the truth of what happened.

author: cersei lannister
content: I don't want a trial. He'll squirm his way to freedom given the chance. I want him dead. Please, Jaime. You have to. He was our son. Our baby boy.

author: jaime lannister
content: You're a hateful woman. Why have the gods made me love a hateful woman?

author: cersei lannister
content: Jaime, not here, please. Please.

author: cersei lannister
content: Stop it. Stop it. Stop.

author: jaime lannister
content: No.

author: cersei lannister
content: Stop it. Stop.

author: cersei lannister
content: Stop. Stop. It's not right.

author: cersei lannister
content: It's not right. It's not right.

author: jaime lannister
content: I don't care.

author: cersei lannister
content: Don't.

author: cersei lannister
content: Don't. Jaime, don't.

author: arya stark
content: Gonna rain soon. Where are we?

author: sandor clegane
content: Near Fairmarket, I think.

author: arya stark
content: You think? You don't have a map?

author: sandor clegane
content: No, I don't have a map.

author: arya stark
content: Maybe we should get one.

author: sandor clegane
content: Just point out the next map shop you see and I'll buy you one.

author: arya stark
content: How far is it to the Eyrie?

author: sandor clegane
content: Far.

author: arya stark
content: And you're sure we're going the right way?

author: sandor clegane
content: Believe me, girl, I want you there as soon as I can. Get my gold, be on my way.

author: arya stark
content: On your way where?

author: sandor clegane
content: Why do you care? Might book passage across the Narrow Sea. Fight as a sellsword. Second Sons, could be. Seems like a good fit for me.

author: arya stark
content: I'd like to see Braavos one day.

author: sandor clegane
content: Why Braavos?

author: arya stark
content: I have friends there.

author: sandor clegane
content: I doubt it.

author: farmer hamlet
content: Seven blessings to you.

author: sandor clegane
content: What do you want?

author: farmer hamlet
content: What do I want? This is my land.

author: sandor clegane
content: If I'm standing on it, it's my land.

author: arya stark
content: We were just watering the horses. We'll be on our way. Forgive my father. He was wounded fighting in the war. Our cottage burned down while he was gone and my mother with it.

author: arya stark
content: He's never been the same.

author: farmer hamlet
content: Which house did he fight for?

author: arya stark
content: The Tullys of Riverrun.

author: farmer hamlet
content: There's a storm coming. You'll be wanting a roof tonight. There's fresh hay in the barn. And Sally here makes rabbit stew just like her mom used to do. We don't have much, but any man that bled for House Tully is welcome to it.

author: farmer hamlet
content: We ask the Father to judge us with mercy accepting our human frailty. We ask the Mother to bless our crops so we may feed ourselves and all who come to our door. We ask the Warrior to give us courage in these days of strife and turmoil. We ask the Maiden to protect Sally's virtue to keep her from the clutches of depravity.

author: sandor clegane
content: You got to do all seven of the fuckers?

author: arya stark
content: Father!

author: farmer hamlet
content: We ask the Smith to strengthen our hands and our backs so we may finish the work required of us. We ask the Crone to guide us on our journey from darkness to darkness.

author: sandor clegane
content: And we ask the Stranger not to kill us in our beds tonight for no damn reason at all.

author: arya stark
content: I'm so sorry.

author: arya stark
content: Really good.

author: farmer hamlet
content: Did you fight at the Twins?

author: sandor clegane
content: Call that a fight? Slaughtering livestock more like.

author: farmer hamlet
content: The Red Wedding they're calling it. Walder Frey committed sacrilege that day. He shared bread and salt with the Starks. He offered them guest right.

author: sandor clegane
content: Guest right don't mean much anymore.

author: farmer hamlet
content: It means something to me. The gods will have their vengeance. Frey will burn in the seventh hell for what he did. Things were different when Hoster Tully ruled the Riverlands. We had good years and bad years, same as anyone. But we were safe. Now with the Freys, raiders come plundering, steal our food, steal our silver. I was gonna send Sally north to stay with my brother, but the north's no better. The whole country's gone sour.

author: sandor clegane
content: You got any ale?

author: farmer hamlet
content: Afraid not.

author: sandor clegane
content: How can a man not keep ale in his home?

author: farmer hamlet
content: You look like you could really swing that sword. A real warrior with proper training. Those raiders wouldn't stand a chance against you. How would it be if you stayed on till the new moon? I could use a man to help with the farmwork. Sally does what she can, but she can't lift a bale of hay. And if any thieves came looking for easy pickings, one look at you, I'd bet they'd run the other way. Meaning no offense.

author: sandor clegane
content: What'll you pay? I don't have much. But I have hidden a bit of silver from the bandits. Fair wages for fair work?

author: sandor clegane
content: Fair wages for fair work.

author: arya stark
content: What did you do?!

author: sandor clegane
content: Get your horse saddled.

author: arya stark
content: You told me you weren't a thief.

author: sandor clegane
content: I wasn't.

author: arya stark
content: He took us in. He fed us and you...

author: sandor clegane
content: Aye, he took us in. He's a good man and his daughter makes a nice stew. And they'll both be dead come winter.

author: arya stark
content: You don't know that.

author: sandor clegane
content: I do know it. He's weak. He can't protect himself. They'll both be dead come winter. Dead men don't need silver.

author: arya stark
content: You're the worst shit in the Seven Kingdoms.

author: sandor clegane
content: There's plenty worse than me. I just understand the way things are. How many Starks they got to behead before you figure it out?

author: ranger
content: Raper. Raper. Horse thief. Ninth born son. Raper. Thief. Thief and raper.

author: alliser thorne
content: There he is, Sam the Slayer.

author: janos slynt
content: Going to visit your wildling whore?

author: sam
content: She's not a whore.

author: janos slynt
content: No? Maybe I'll give her a copper tonight and find out.

author: sam
content: They all think I'm lying.

author: gilly
content: About what?

author: sam
content: Killing the white Walker.

author: gilly
content: You're not lying. I'll never forget the way it screamed.

author: sam
content: But you're the only one that saw it. And they all think you're just a...

author: gilly
content: A what?

author: sam
content: Well, a wildling.

author: gilly
content: My father hated that word.

author: sam
content: It's not a very nice word, I suppose.

author: gilly
content: I don't know. It makes me sound a bit dangerous, doesn't it?

author: sam
content: So... are you all right? No one bothering you?

author: gilly
content: I get a lot of looks. I hear them making their jokes. But no one's touched me if that's what you mean.

author: sam
content: I worry about it sometimes. All the time.

author: gilly
content: Why do you worry about it?

author: sam
content: 100 men, one woman.

author: gilly
content: They've got other things to think about.

author: sam
content: That's the only thing they think about.

author: gilly
content: You're being silly.

author: sam
content: I'm not being silly. There's 100 men lying awake at night picturing you.

author: gilly
content: What about you?

author: sam
content: What about me? Gilly? I worry about you.

author: gilly
content: Thank you.

author: sam
content: For what?

author: gilly
content: For worrying about me.

author: sam
content: I don't know if you're safe here. They're my brothers, but some of them were thieves before they came here. Some of them were rapers. You saw what they did at your father's keep.

author: gilly
content: So what are you saying?

author: sam
content: Maybe you'd be safer in Mole's Town.

author: gilly
content: Are you bored of me?

author: sam
content: Bored of you? I... I want to protect you.

author: gilly
content: I'll get these to Hobb. Keep an eye on little Sam.

author: davos
content: Your Grace.

author: stannis baratheon
content: You're a literary man now. What do you make of that?

author: davos
content: Joffrey?

author: stannis baratheon
content: The usurper Joffrey Baratheon. I said those words when I tossed a leech into the fire. A leech filled with bastard blood. A bastard you set free. I am now faced with a great opportunity and I am powerless to take advantage of it.

author: davos
content: I will find you an army, Your Grace. I've been working day and night...

author: stannis baratheon
content: What progress have you made?

author: davos
content: I've rallied House Peasebury to your 'cause.

author: stannis baratheon
content: House Peasebury.

author: davos
content: House Musgood.

author: stannis baratheon
content: House Musgood.

author: davos
content: And House Haigh.

author: stannis baratheon
content: House Haigh. They don't have enough men between them to raid a pantry.

author: davos
content: Westeros is not the world, Your Grace. We need to look east for ships and men. 10,000 skilled soldiers fight for the Golden Company.

author: stannis baratheon
content: The Golden Company?

author: davos
content: They've never broken a contract.

author: stannis baratheon
content: They're sellswords.

author: davos
content: We're willing to use blood magic to put you on the throne, but we're not willing to pay men to fight? Now the Red Woman's magic is real. Her visions and prophecies may be, too, but I've never heard of visions and prophecies winning a war. Soldiers win wars. Soldiers on the ground. It's dirty on the ground.

author: stannis baratheon
content: We don't have any gold.

author: davos
content: Not yet.

author: stannis baratheon
content: If I do not press my claim, my claim will be forgotten. I will not become a page in someone else's history book. I'm running out of time, Ser Davos. Which means you're running out of time. -

author: shireen
content: You're late.

author: davos
content: I'm sorry, Princess.

author: shireen
content: I thought you weren't coming.

author: davos
content: The Hand of the King doesn't have much leisure time.

author: shireen
content: You won't be a very good Hand if you see the word knight and say "ka-nigit."

author: davos
content: That happened once, weeks ago. You're your father's daughter, no mistake. Bloody relentless, the both of you.

author: shireen
content: It's a new one today. Lots of tricky words. But I think you can manage.

author: shireen
content: You'll never read well if you move your lips. That's how children do it.

author: davos
content: The Life and Adventures of Elyo Grivas. First Sword of Braavos.

author: davos
content: Thank you very much.

author: shireen
content: I like this one. It's full of sword fights and pirates. You were a pirate once.

author: davos
content: No, I was never a pirate. I was a smuggler.

author: shireen
content: What's the difference?

author: davos
content: Well, if you're a famous smuggler, you're not doing it right.

author: shireen
content: My father says a criminal is a criminal.

author: davos
content: Your father lacks an appreciation of the finer points of bad behavior. So do the Braavosi.

author: shireen
content: You've sailed to Braavos?

author: davos
content: Of course. Almost got beheaded by a First Sword of Braavos. I tried to explain to him the difference between pirates and smugglers, but he didn't seem any more interested in the distinction than your father. I suppose if you work for the Iron Bank of Braavos and each one of your gold barges is worth half a kingdom, you tend not to be overly concerned with the kind of distinction...

author: shireen
content: What was that for?

author: davos
content: I need you to write a message.

author: shireen
content: You should write it yourself. It's good practice.

author: davos
content: It's too important for me. I need a smart person to do it. Go on.

author: davos
content: To the offices of the Iron Bank of Braavos from Stannis Baratheon the one true king of Westeros.

author: shireen
content: But that's not you.

author: davos
content: I need to get their attention. Go on. Write.

author: sam
content: He's seen some adventures, hasn't he?

author: moles town whore
content: Precious little thing.

author: moles town whore
content: What's his name?

author: gilly
content: Sam.

author: moles town whore
content: Lovely. That the daddy?

author: gilly
content: No.

author: moles town whore
content: Where's the daddy?

author: gilly
content: He's dead.

author: moles town whore
content: Oh. Where you from?

author: gilly
content: North of here.

author: moles town whore
content: North of here? You a fucking wildling?

author: moles town madam
content: Only room and board?

author: sam
content: That's right. She'll clean and cook and look after the other girls' babies.

author: moles town madam
content: Could find other work for her, too.

author: sam
content: No other work.

author: moles town madam
content: There'd be money. Give you a piece of it.

author: sam
content: I promise to come back and visit whenever I can. You'll be safer here. Who's gonna protect you at Castle Black? Me?

author: gilly
content: You protected me north of the Wall.

author: sam
content: This is different. They're brothers of the Night's Watch and I can't just stab them in the back and I can't run away, which is what we did at Craster's.

author: sam
content: You have to trust me. It's for the best.

author: gilly
content: Best for you.

author: sam
content: Oh, Gilly. Please don't.

author: oberyn martell
content: Greedy.

author: ellaria
content: No?

author: olyvar
content: I'm sorry. You're lovely, I just never acquired the taste.

author: oberyn martell
content: You're calling my beauty an acquired taste?

author: ellaria
content: That's quite all right, lover. It's more for you.

author: oberyn martell
content: Your loss.

author: olyvar
content: You like them both the same? Boys and girls?

author: oberyn martell
content: Does that surprise you?

author: olyvar
content: Everyone has a preference.

author: oberyn martell
content: Then everyone is missing half the worldo s pleasure. The gods made that and it delights me. The gods made this and it delights me. When it comes to war, I fight for Dorne. When it comes to love, I don't choose sides.

author: olyvar
content: I hope I have as much stamina when I'm your age.

author: oberyn martell
content: What are you, 25?

author: ellaria
content: Children.

author: oberyn martell
content: Someday, if you're lucky, you will wake up and realize you are old. That pretty ass of yours will sag. Your belly will grow soft and your back will ache in the night and gray hairs will sprout from your ears. No one will want you anymore. Make sure you fucked your fill before that day.

author: olyvar
content: Did you?

author: ellaria
content: He is a prince of Dorne. Girls and boys will line up to fuck him till the day he dies.

author: oberyn martell
content: They will all have to line up behind you.

author: tywin lannister
content: Prince Oberyn.

author: oberyn martell
content: Lord Tywin.

author: tywin lannister
content: May we have the room?

author: ellaria
content: Call my name if you need me, lover.

author: oberyn martell
content: Would you like to sit?

author: tywin lannister
content: No, thank you.

author: oberyn martell
content: Some wine?

author: oberyn martell
content: I'm sorry about your grandson.

author: tywin lannister
content: Are you?

author: oberyn martell
content: I don't believe that a child is responsible for the sins of his father. Or his grandfather. An awful way to die.

author: tywin lannister
content: Which way is that?

author: oberyn martell
content: Are you interrogating me, Lord Tywin?

author: tywin lannister
content: Some believe the king choked.

author: oberyn martell
content: Some believe the sky is blue because we live inside the eye of a blue-eyed giant. The king was poisoned.

author: tywin lannister
content: I hear you studied poisons at the Citadel.

author: oberyn martell
content: I did. This is why I know.

author: tywin lannister
content: Your hatred for my family is rather well known. You arrive at the capital, an expert in poisoning, some days later my grandson dies of poisoning.

author: oberyn martell
content: Rather suspicious. Why haven't you thrown me in a dungeon?

author: tywin lannister
content: You spoke with Tyrion in this very brothel on the day that you arrived. What did you discuss?

author: oberyn martell
content: You think we conspired together?

author: tywin lannister
content: What did you discuss?

author: oberyn martell
content: The death of my sister.

author: tywin lannister
content: For which you blame me.

author: oberyn martell
content: She was raped and murdered by the Mountain. The Mountain follows your orders. Of course I blame you.

author: tywin lannister
content: Here I stand unarmed, unguarded. Should I be concerned?

author: oberyn martell
content: You are unarmed and unguarded because you know me better than that. I am a man of reason. If I cut your throat today, I will be drawn and quartered tomorrow.

author: tywin lannister
content: Men at war commit all kinds of crimes without their superiors' knowledge.

author: oberyn martell
content: So you deny involvement in Elia's murder?

author: tywin lannister
content: Categorically.

author: oberyn martell
content: I would like to speak with the Mountain.

author: tywin lannister
content: I'm sure he would enjoy speaking with you.

author: oberyn martell
content: He might not enjoy it as much as he thinks he would.

author: tywin lannister
content: I could arrange for this meeting.

author: oberyn martell
content: But you want something in return.

author: tywin lannister
content: There will be a trial for my son. And as custom dictates, three judges will render a verdict. I will preside. Mace Tyrell will serve as the second judge. I would like you to be the third.

author: oberyn martell
content: Why?

author: tywin lannister
content: Not long ago, the Tyrells sided with Renly Baratheon. Declared themselves enemies of the throne. Now they are our strongest allies.

author: oberyn martell
content: Well, you made the Tyrell girl a queen. Asking me to judge at your son's trial isn't quite as tempting.

author: tywin lannister
content: I will also invite you to sit on the small council to serve as one of the new king's principal advisors.

author: oberyn martell
content: I never realized you had such respect for Dorne, Lord Tywin.

author: tywin lannister
content: We are not the Seven Kingdoms until Dorne returns to the fold. The king is dead. The Greyjoys are in open rebellion. A wildling army marches on the Wall. And in the East, a Targaryen girl has three dragons. Before long, she will turn her eyes to Westeros. Only the Dornish managed to resist Aegon Targaryen and his dragons.

author: oberyn martell
content: You're saying you need us? That must be hard for you to admit.

author: tywin lannister
content: We need each other. You help me serve justice to the king's assassins and I will help you serve justice to Elia's.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Podrick. Apologies for the stench.

author: podrick
content: I brought you some wine, my lord, but they took it from me.

author: tyrion lannister
content: A noble effort.

author: podrick
content: They didn't find the candles, though. A quill, some parchment, duck sausage, almonds, and some hard cheese.

author: tyrion lannister
content: You're a good lad. Any word of Shae?

author: podrick
content: I've heard nothing, my lord.

author: tyrion lannister
content: I suppose that's a good thing. What are they saying about me out there?

author: podrick
content: You're to stand trial in a fortnight for murdering the king.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Do you believe I murdered Joffrey?

author: podrick
content: No, my lord. You didn't?

author: tyrion lannister
content: No. Gods, no. The world is a better place without him, but I had nothing to do with it. I would like to think if I were arranging a royal assassination, I'd plan it in such a way that I wouldn't be standing there gawking like a fool when the king died. Trial in a fortnight. Have they announced the judges yet?

author: podrick
content: Your father.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Of course.

author: podrick
content: Mace Tyrell.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Who will vote exactly as my father tells him to vote.

author: podrick
content: And Prince Oberyn of Dorne.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Oberyn? Give it to my father. He never fails to take advantage of a family tragedy.

author: podrick
content: I'm supposed to get a list of names from you, my lord. Anyone who might testify on your behalf.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Oh, I can call my own witnesses? How generous of them. Very well, my wife. Sansa.

author: podrick
content: My lord, she's gone.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Gone?

author: podrick
content: No one's seen her since the wedding. You don't think she...

author: tyrion lannister
content: No one had more 'cause to kill Joffrey than Sansa, but the girl is no assassin. Whoever killed the king wanted me to lose my head for it. And with my wife's disappearance, it makes me seem that much more guilty. Podrick.

author: podrick
content: Yes, my lord?

author: tyrion lannister
content: They'll be following you now.

author: podrick
content: Who will?

author: tyrion lannister
content: I don't know. They. They. The ominous they. The man pulling the strings. Or woman. My father. Maybe Joffrey was too much work for him. Sweet Tommen will be so much easier to handle. Whenever something bad happens to me, I assume it's my sister that had a hand in it. But say what you will of Cersei, she loves her children. She is the only one I'm certain had nothing to do with this murder. Which makes it unique as King's Landing murders go.

author: podrick
content: Any other witnesses, my lord?

author: tyrion lannister
content: Varys could vouch for me if he dared.

author: podrick
content: He's already been called as a witness for the queen.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Of course. Fetch Bronn. I have a job for him.

author: podrick
content: I've already asked, my lord. They won't let him see you.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Why not?

author: podrick
content: They say he's a known cutthroat and your close associate. He's under investigation himself.

author: tyrion lannister
content: And my brother? Will they at least allow me to see Jaime?

author: podrick
content: I'll ask, my lord.

author: podrick
content: There's something else, my lord. A man, I didn't know his face, he came to ask if I'd testify against you. Said I'd be named Ser Podrick Payne if I told the judges you'd bought a poison called the Strangler.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Ser Podrick Payne? Has a nice ring to it. What did you tell him?

author: podrick
content: I didn't tell them anything, my lord.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Are you going to accept their offer?

author: podrick
content: My lord.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Testifying against me wasn't a suggestion. If they can't tempt you with honey, they'll choose something less sweet.

author: podrick
content: You've been good to me, my lord.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Pod, the trial's in a fortnight. They'll want an answer before that.

author: podrick
content: I already gave them an answer, my lord.

author: tyrion lannister
content: I will not have you dying on my behalf. Do you hear me? If I have to take that long walk to the executioner's block, I don't want to see your head already mounted.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Pod, I am giving you an order. Go and find my brother. Tell him I need him. And get yourself out of King's Landing before it's too late. Pod! This is farewell.

author: podrick
content: Farewell, my lord.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Pod. There has never lived a more loyal squire.

author: olly
content: Mother says it's time to eat.

author: guymon
content: What's she got boiling? Wait. Wait. Let me guess.

author: olly
content: Potatoes.

author: guymon
content: Potatoes. Well, no one boils a potato better than your mom. Has she got...

author: man
content: The wildlings!

author: ollys mother
content: Guymon! Hide. Hide!

author: styr
content: You know how to get to Castle Black?

author: olly
content: Yes. Yes.

author: styr
content: Those your parents? Open your eyes. I'm going to eat them. Do you hear me? I'm going to eat your dead mama and I'm going to eat your dead papa. Go tell the crows at Castle Black.

author: yarwyck
content: We need to teach them a lesson about the way we deal with their kind.

author: men
content: Aye! Aye!

author: yarwyck
content: Three dozen bodies with slit throats tossed off the top of the Wall. Seems like that would be a good lesson.

author: men
content: Aye!

author: alliser thorne
content: If we go after them, we'll be giving them what they want. They want to draw us out, pick us off a few at a time.

author: maester aemon
content: We have just over 100 men. And that's including stewards and builders. And me. We can't afford to lose a single man. We must remember our first responsibility. We are the watchers on the Wall.

author: pyp
content: There's got to be a way to protect them.

author: alliser thorne
content: You're a champion of the common people, Lord Snow. What do you say to Brother Pyp's proposition?

author: jon snow
content: Mance Rayder is coming. If the wildlings breach the Wall, they'll roll over everything and everyone for 1,000 Miles before they reach an army that can stop them.

author: alliser thorne
content: We need to shore up Castle Black and we need to defend the Wall. That is our job.

author: pyp
content: Rangers returning.

author: jon snow
content: Help him.

author: dolorous edd
content: Thought you'd have blue eyes by now.

author: alliser thorn
content: What took you so long?

author: grenn
content: We were held up.

author: alliser thorn
content: By what?

author: grenn
content: Chains.

author: dolorous edd
content: We were guests of the mutineers at Craster's Keep.

author: jon snow
content: And the mutineers stayed?

author: dolorous edd
content: They're not going anywhere. They've got Craster's food and his wives. Poor girls. Never thought they'd miss their daddy. Karl's running things now. He's the one who put a knife through Craster's mouth.

author: jon snow
content: We need to ride north and kill them all.

author: alliser thorn
content: We just went over this, boy. -Justice can wait.

author: jon snow
content: It's not about justice. I told the wildlings we had over 1,000 men at Castle Black alone. Karl and the others know the truth as well as we do. How long do you think they'll keep that information to themselves when the wildlings are peeling their fingernails off? Mance has all he needs to crush us, he just doesn't know it yet. As soon as he gets his hands on them, he will. Then he'll throw his full strength at us. And even if every one of us kills 100 wildlings, there's still not a thing we can do to stop them.

author: pyp
content: I don't think I can kill 100 wildlings.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Are they attacking?

author: jorah mormont
content: A single rider. A champion of Meereen. They want you to send your own champion against him.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: What is he doing?

author: barristan selmy
content: I believe he means to...

author: missandei
content: He says that we're an army of men without man parts. He claims you are no woman at all, but a man who... hides his cock in his own asshole.

author: barristan selmy
content: Ignore him, Your Grace. These are meaningless words.

author: jorah mormont
content: They're not meaningless if half the city you intend to take is listening to them.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: I have something to say to the people of Meereen. First, I will need this one to be quiet. Do I have a champion?

author: grey worm
content: Allow me this honor, mother of dragons. I will not disappoint you.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: You are the commander of the Unsullied. I cannot risk you.

author: barristan selmy
content: Your Grace, I've won more single combats than any man alive.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Which is why you must remain by my side.

author: jorah mormont
content: I've been by your side longer than any of them, Khaleesi. Let me stand for you today as well.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: You are my most trusted advisor, my most valued general, and my dearest friend. I will not gamble with your life.

author: daario
content: I was the last to join your army. I'm not your general or a member of your Queensguard or the commander of your Unsullied. My mother was a whore. I come from nothing. And before long, I will return to nothing. Let me kill this man for you.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Very well. You have quite an audience. Make it worth their while.

author: missandei
content: He is very brave, Your Grace.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Yes, win or lose, as long as the whole city is watching.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: You sure you don't want a horse?

author: daario
content: Why would I want a horse?

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Horses are faster than men.

author: daario
content: Horses are dumber than men.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: I am Daenerys Stormborn.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Your Masters may have told you lies about me, or they may have told you nothing. It does not matter. I have nothing to say to them. Only to you. First I went to Astapor. Those who were slaves in Astapor now stand behind me, free. Next I went to Yunkai. Those who were slaves in Yunkai now stand behind me, free. Now I have come to Meereen. I am not your enemy. Your enemy is beside you.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Your enemy steals and murders your children. Your enemy has nothing for you but chains and suffering and commands. I do not bring commands. I bring you a choice. And I bring your enemies what they deserve. Forward!

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Fire!

author: grey worm
content: My name is Grey Worm. I come from the Summer "Ills."

author: missandei
content: Isles. Summer Isles.

author: grey worm
content: Summer Isles.

author: missandei
content: I am from an island called Naath.

author: grey worm
content: When they took you?

author: missandei
content: When did they take me?" I was five years old.

author: grey worm
content: You remember your home?

author: missandei
content: I remember when they rowed us away from shore. How white the beaches were. How tall the trees. And I remember my village burning. Smoke rising into the sky. Do you remember your home?

author: grey worm
content: Unsullied. Always Unsullied. Before Unsullied, nothing.

author: missandei
content: That's not true. Perhaps one day you will return to the Summer Isles.

author: grey worm
content: I don't want return.

author: missandei
content: Kill the masters.

author: grey worm
content: Kill the masters.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: How are the lessons coming?

author: missandei
content: Very well, Your Grace.

author: grey worm
content: Missandei is teacher good, my queen.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: You'll have to continue later. It's time.

author: mossador
content: You heard her! She said she came to free us.

author: elder meereen slave
content: You are a fool. The masters are too strong.

author: mossador
content: She will protect us. She defeated the masters' champion.

author: mossador
content: She has a great army. You want to live the rest of your days in chains?

author: meereen slave
content: I want to live. You saw what they did to those children. What do you think they'll do to us?

author: elder meereen slave
content: I've been through two slave revolts, boy. They always end the same way

author: grey worm
content: All men must die.

author: grey worm
content: But I promise you, a single day of freedom is worth more than a lifetime in chains.

author: elder meereen slave
content: Who are you?

author: grey worm
content: This one is called Grey Worm. I was taken as a baby by the Masters of Astapor, raised and trained as Unsullied. Now I fight for Daenerys, the Mother of Dragons and Breaker of Chains.

author: elder meereen slave
content: You are Unsullied? They taught you how to fight before you could walk. We are not soldiers.

author: meereen slave
content: We have no training, weapons.

author: grey worm
content: There are three slaves in this city for every Master. No one can give you your freedom, brothers. If you want it, you must take it.

author: slaves
content: Mhysa! Mhysa! Mhysa!

author: slaves
content: Mhysa! Mhysa! Mhysa! Mhysa!

author: slaves
content: Mhysa! Mhysa!

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Remind me, Ser Jorah, how many children did the Great Masters nail to mileposts?

author: jorah mormont
content: 163, Khaleesi.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Yes, that was it.

author: barristan selmy
content: Your Grace, may I have a word? The city is yours. All these people,they're your subjects now. Sometimes it is better to answer injustice with mercy.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: I will answer injustice with justice.

author: jaime lannister
content: What the hell was that?

author: bronn
content: That was me knocking your ass to the dirt with your own hand.

author: jaime lannister
content: You're a rare talent. When you're fighting cripples, anyway.

author: bronn
content: You learned to fight like a good little boy. I'll bet that thrust through the MadKing's back was pretty as a picture. You want to fight pretty or you want to win?

author: jaime lannister
content: You talk to my brother this way?

author: bronn
content: All the time. He got used to it.

author: jaime lannister
content: Do you think he did it?

author: bronn
content: No. Oh, he hated the little twat, sure. But who didn't? And poison's not his style. Or murder, for that matter. You want to know for sure, why don't you ask him?

author: bronn
content: You haven't been to see him yet, eh?

author: jaime lannister
content: We're done for today.

author: bronn
content: Your brother ever tell you how I came into his service?

author: jaime lannister
content: You stood for him in his trial by combat at the Eyrie.

author: bronn
content: Aye. But only when Lady Arryn demanded the trial take place that day. You were his first choice. He named you for his champion because he knew you would ride day and night to come fight for him. You gonna fight for him now?

author: jaime lannister
content: To tell you the truth, this isn't so bad. Four walls. A pot to piss in. I was chained to a wooden post covered in my own shit for months.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Is that supposed to make me feel better?

author: jaime lannister
content: Maybe a bit. I'm sorry I didn't come sooner.

author: tyrion lannister
content: It's complicated, yes. So how is our sister?

author: jaime lannister
content: How do you think? Her son died in her arms.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Her son?

author: jaime lannister
content: Don't. You know what's coming?

author: tyrion lannister
content: My trial for regicide.Yes, I know. I know the whole bloody country thinks I'm guilty. I know that one of my three judges has wished me dead more times than I can count. And that judge is my father. As for Cersei, well, she's probably working on a way to avoid a trial altogether by having me killed.

author: jaime lannister
content: Now that you mention it, she did ask.

author: tyrion lannister
content: So, should I turn around and close my eyes?

author: jaime lannister
content: Depends. Did you do it?

author: tyrion lannister
content: The Kingslayer brothers. You like it? I like it. You're really asking if I killed your son?

author: jaime lannister
content: Are you really asking if I'd kill my brother? How can I help you?

author: tyrion lannister
content: Well, you could set me free.

author: jaime lannister
content: You know I can't.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Then there's really nothing else to say.

author: jaime lannister
content: What do you want me to do? Kill the guards? Sneak you out of the city in the back of a cart? I'm the Lord Commander of the Kingsguard.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Sorry, I'd forgotten. I'd hate for you to do something inappropriate.

author: jaime lannister
content: Inappropriate? You're accused of killing the king.Freeing you is treason.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Except I didn't do it.

author: jaime lannister
content: Which is why we're having a trial. A trial. If the killer threw himself before the Iron Throne, confessed to his crimes, and gave irrefutable evidence of his guilt, it wouldn't matter to Cersei. She won't rest until my heado s on a spike.

author: jaime lannister
content: Not just yours. She's offering a knighthood to whomever finds Sansa Stark.

author: tyrion lannister
content: Sansa couldn't have done this. She had more reason than anyone in the Seven Kingdoms. Do you think it's a coincidence she disappeared the same night Joffrey died?

author: tyrion lannister
content: No, but... Sansa's not a killer. Not yet, anyway.

author: sansa stark
content: Where are you taking me?

author: petyr baelish
content: I'm getting married to your Aunt Lysa. She's waiting for us at the Eyrie. You'll be safe there.

author: sansa stark
content: Did you kill Joffrey?

author: petyr baelish
content: Did I kill Joffrey? I've been in the Vale for weeks.

author: sansa stark
content: I know it was you.

author: petyr baelish
content: And who helped me with this conspiracy?

author: sansa stark
content: Well, there was Ser Dontos. You used him to get me out of King's Landing, but you would never trust him to kill the king.

author: petyr baelish
content: Why not?

author: sansa stark
content: Because you're too smart to trust a drunk.

author: petyr baelish
content: Then perhaps it was your husband.

author: sansa stark
content: No.

author: petyr baelish
content: How do you know?

author: sansa stark
content: I just do.

author: petyr baelish
content: You're right. He wasn't involvedi n Joffrey's death. But you were. Do you remember that lovely necklace Dontos gave you? I don't suppose you noticed that a stone was missing after the feast.

author: sansa stark
content: The poison. I don't understand. The Lannisters gave you wealth, power. Joffrey made you the Lord of Harrenhal.

author: petyr baelish
content: A man with no motive is a man no one suspects. Always keep your foes confused. If they don't know who you are or what you want, they can't know what you plan to do next.

author: sansa stark
content: I don't believe you. If they catch you, they'll put your head on a spike just like my father's. You'd risk that just to confuse them?

author: petyr baelish
content: So many men they risk so little. They spend their lives avoiding danger. And then they die. I'd risk everything to get what I want.

author: sansa stark
content: And what do you want?

author: petyr baelish
content: Everything. My friendship with the Lannisters was productive. But Joffrey, a vicious boy with a crown on his head, is not a reliable ally. And who could trust a friend like that?

author: sansa stark
content: Who could trust you?

author: petyr baelish
content: I don't want friends like me. My new friends are predictable. Very reasonable people. As for what happened to Joffrey, well, that was something my new friends wanted very badly. Nothing like a thoughtful gift to make a new friendship grow strong.

author: margaery tyrell
content: I can't believe you're going. Leaving me alone here with these people.

author: olenna tyrell
content: The time has come, my dear. There's nothing more tedious than a trial. Except perhaps these gardens. If I have to take one more leisurely stroll through these gardens, I'll fling myself from the cliffs.

author: olenna tyrell
content: Have you been to see Tommen yet?

author: margaery tyrell
content: No. Have they even agreed to the match? No one tells me anything.

author: olenna tyrell
content: I wasn't originally meant to marry your grandfather Luthor, you know. He was engaged to my sister, your great-aunt Viola. I was to be given to some Targaryen or other. Marrying a Targaryen was all the rage back then. But the momentI saw my intended, with his twitchy little ferret's face and ludicrous silver hair, I knew he wouldn't do. So the evening before Luthor was to propose to my sister, I got lost on my way back from my embroidery lesson and happened upon his chamber.

author: olenna tyrell
content: How absentminded of me.

author: margaery tyrell
content: Mm-hmm.

author: olenna tyrell
content: The following morning, Luthor never made it down the stairs to propose to my sister 'cause the boy couldn't bloody walk.

author: olenna tyrell
content: And once he could, the only thing he wanted was what I'd given him the night before. I was good. I was very, very good. You are even better. But you need to act quickly. Cersei may be vicious, but she's not stupid. She'll turn the boy against you as soon as she can. And by the time you're married, it'll be too late. Luckily for you ,the Queen Regent is rather distracted at the moment, mourning her dear departed boy. Accusing her brother of his murder, which he didn't commit.

author: margaery tyrell
content: Well, he could have done.

author: olenna tyrell
content: He could have done,but he didn't.

author: margaery tyrell
content: You don't know, Grandmother.

author: olenna tyrell
content: But I do know. You don't think I'd let you marry that beast, do you?

author: margaery tyrell
content: What? I don't understand.

author: olenna tyrell
content: Shh. Don't you worry yourself about all that. You just do what needs to be done.

author: jon snow
content: Bring it through! And again.

author: jon snow
content: Very nice. Good.

author: jon snow
content: A lot of wildlings fight with a weapon in each hand. First thing you want to do is disarm them to try and even the odds.

author: jon snow
content: Let's see what you can do.

author: jon snow
content: Olly, you just watch for now.

author: olly
content: I can fight.

author: jon snow
content: Have you ever held a sword before? OLLY I was the best archer in our hamlet.

author: olly
content: I was!

author: grenn
content: I believe you. We'll go hunting for rabbits one day. Right now, watch and learn.

author: jon snow
content: You two. Take it slow, try and disarm each other.

author: jon snow
content: You know how to fight. You could have gone easier on him.

author: locke
content: He wouldn't have learned anything that way.

author: alliser thorne
content: Lord Snow. What do you think you're doing?

author: jon snow
content: Grenn and I were helping them.

author: alliser thorn
content: Grenn's a ranger.You're a steward. Maybe you forgot that while you were off with your wildling bitch, but I didn't.

author: jon snow
content: Someone has to train them.

author: alliser thorne
content: And that someone isn't you. Go find a chamber pot to empty. Go on. Do it. You traitor's bastard. Give me an excuse. Mormont's not hereto protect you now.

author: alliser thorne
content: Get back to work. Now! I said now!

author: janos slynt
content: The bastardo s well-liked.You're not.

author: alliser thorne
content: You think I care if they like me? We're at war.

author: janos slynt
content: For now. But you can't be acting commander forever. There will be a choosing. The old maester will insist on it. You might reconsider his request to marchon Craster's. Let the mutineer stake care of Snow. Or you might be taking orders from him the rest of your life.

author: locke
content: A bastard, eh? Took you for highborn.

author: jon snow
content: My father was highborn. My mother wasn't.

author: locke
content: Name's Locke.

author: jon snow
content: Jon Snow.

author: jon snow
content: You fight well.

author: locke
content: What brought you up here? A sense of duty. I wanted to do my part for the safety of the realm. I was a game warden in the Stormlands. Fed a prized partridge to my hungry kids. I was stupid enough to get caught. Chose the Wall over losing my hand. Figured I wouldn't have to suck up to any highborn cunts here.

author: alliser thorne
content: Come on, get on with it. What are you waiting for? Summer?

author: locke
content: Guess I was wrong.

author: jaime lannister
content: You sent for me, Your Grace?

author: cersei lannister
content: Your Grace. How formal of you. How many Kingsguards are posted outside Tommen's door?

author: jaime lannister
content: Ser Boros is on duty tonight. Tomorrow I believe...

author: cersei lannister

author: cersei lannister

author: margaery tyrell
content: I'm not a visitor, Your Grace. Word has itI'm to be your bride.

author: margaery tyrell
content: Did you know that people in arranged marriages often never meet until their wedding day? Before we decide to spend our lives together, we ought to get to know one another. Don't you think?

author: tommen lannister
content: Yes. But if my mother found out...

author: margaery tyrell
content: It can be our secret. Hmm? If we're going to be man and wife, we'll have a few secrets from her, I hope. So, Your Grace...

author: tommen lannister
content: Yes? Tell me a secret.

author: margaery tyrell
content: Hello. Aren't you a proper fellow?

author: tommen lannister
content: That's Ser Pounce.

author: margaery tyrell
content: Very handsome.

author: tommen lannister
content: Joffrey didn't like him. He threatened to skin him alive and mix his innards up in my food so I wouldn't know I was eating him.

author: margaery tyrell
content: That's very cruel. You don't strike me as cruel.

author: tommen lannister
content: No. I don't think I am.

author: margaery tyrell
content: That's a relief. Because you know what happens when we marry?

author: tommen lannister
content: We say our vows in front of the High Septon. And after the ceremony, there's a feast.

author: margaery tyrell
content: When we marry, I become yours. Forever. It's getting late. I should go. May I come and visit you again? All right, then.

author: margaery tyrell
content: Remember, our little secret.

author: brienne

Arya's probably dead, too, but there's still a chance to find Sansa and get her somewhere safe. I've got something else for you.

author: jaime lannister
content: I hope I got your measurements right.

author: brienne

author: sam

author: sam

author: alliser thorne
content: Your foray to Craster's Keep, I'll sanction it. But I won't order anyone to go with you. Volunteers only.

author: jon snow

author: jon snow
content: Ahem, brothers.

author: jon snow
content: I'm going beyond the Wallto Craster's Keep. I'm going to capture the mutineers holed up there or kill them. I'm asking for volunteers to come with me. There's 60 miles of wilderness between here and Craster's and Mance Rayder has an army bearing down on us, but we have to do this. Our survival may depend on us getting to these mutineers before Mance does. They know the Wall. They know our defenses. If Mance learns what they know, we're lost. But if that's not enough, then consider this. If the Night's Watch are truly brothers, then Lord Commander Mormont was our father. He lived and died for the Watch and he was betrayed by his own men. Stabbed in the back by cowards. He deserved far better. All we can give him now is justice. Who will join me?

author: jon snow
content: I can't let a recruit come north of the Wall.

author: locke
content: Then let me say my vows. If it's a fight you're heading for, then you need men who know how.

author: jon snow
content: Thank you, brothers.

content: Fuck!

author: tanner

content: You see, where I come from, a commoner like me slaps a little lord like you, I'd lose my right hand. But we're a long way from home, aren't we? And the two of you, fancy-looking folks north of the Wall creeping through the woods. Isn't that a bit odd?

author: septon
content: May the Warrior grant him courage and protect him in these perilous times. May the Smith grant him strength that he might bear this heavy burden. And may the Crone, she that knows the fate of all men, show him the path he must walk and guide him through the dark places that lie ahead. In the light of the Seven, I now proclaim Tommen of the House Baratheon First of His Name. King of the Andals and the First Men and Lord of the Seven Kingdoms. Long may he reign!

author: all
content: Long may he reign!

author: septon
content: Special day.

author: pycelle
content: Your Grace.

author: varys
content: Your Grace.

author: man
content: Your Grace.

author: margaery tyrell
content: Your Grace.

author: cersei lannister
content: There he is.

author: margaery tyrell
content: Long may he reign.

author: cersei lannister
content: Long may he reign.

author: margaery tyrell
content: He sits the throne like he was born to it.

author: cersei lannister
content: Yes. He wasn't, though, was he?

author: margaery tyrell
content: No, he wasn't.

author: cersei lannister
content: You still mourn for Joffrey?

author: margaery tyrell
content: He was my husband. My king.

author: cersei lannister
content: He would have been your nightmare.

author: margaery tyrell
content: Your Grace, I feel...

author: cersei lannister
content: You knew exactly what he was. I did, too. You never love anything in the world the way you love your first child. Doesn't matter what they do. And what he did, it shocked me. Do you think I'm easily shocked?

author: margaery tyrell
content: No.

author: cersei lannister
content: The things he did shocked me. He's only a boy. A good boy. A decent boy. He always has been. Who was the last decent king, I wonder? He could be the first man who sits on that throne in fifty years to actually deserve it.

author: margaery tyrell
content: It would be some consolation, wouldn't it? For all the horror that put him there.

author: cersei lannister
content: He will need help... if he's going to rule well.

author: margaery tyrell
content: He has you.

author: cersei lannister
content: A mother is not enough. You're still interested in being queen, I take it?

author: margaery tyrell
content: Oh. After all that's happened... It sounds strange, I know, but I am... I haven't even given any thought to it, what comes next. It would be a great honor, of course. But I will have to speak to my father about it.

author: cersei lannister
content: Yes, speak to your father. I'll speak to mine.

author: margaery tyrell
content: We may be faced with an alarming number of weddings soon.

author: margaery tyrell
content: I won't even know what to call you. Sister? Or Mother? Hmm.

author: jorah mormont
content: King Joffrey Baratheon is dead. Murdered at his own wedding.

author: barristan
content: And we have taken the Meereenese Navy, Your Grace.

author: daario
content: The Second Sons took the Meereenese Navy.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Who told you to take the Navy?

author: daario
content: No one.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: So why did you do it?

author: daario
content: I heard you liked ships.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: How many ships?

author: barristan
content: Ninety-three, Your Grace.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: How many men can they carry?

author: barristan
content: Ninety-three hundred, not counting sailors.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Would that be enough to take King's Landing?

author: jorah mormont
content: The Lannisters have more.

author: barristan
content: They've been fighting Joffrey's wars for years. They're tired, dispersed. And now their king is dead. Eight thousand Unsullied, two thousand Second Sons sailing into Blackwater Bay and storming the gates without warning.

author: jorah mormont
content: It's hard to say. It could be enough. But we're not fighting to make you Queen of King's Landing. Ten thousand men can't conquer Westeros.

author: barristan
content: The old houses will flock to our queen when she crosses the Narrow Sea.

author: jorah mormont
content: The old houses will flock to whichever side they think will win, as they always have.

author: jorah mormont
content: There's other news. From Yunkai. Without the Unsullied to enforce your rule, the Wise Masters have retaken control of the city. They've re-enslaved the freedmen who stayed behind and sworn to take revenge against you. And in Astapor, the council you installed to rule over the city has been overthrown by a butcher named Cleon who's declared himself "His Imperial Majesty."

author: daenerys targaryen
content: Please leave me. Not you, Jorah.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: It appears my liberation of Slaver's Bay isn't going quite as planned.

author: jorah mormont
content: You could sail for Westeros and leave it all behind. A boy sits on the Iron Throne. A boy many believe to be a bastard with no right to it. They've never been more vulnerable.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: You counseled me against rashness once in Qarth. I didn't listen. That all worked out well.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: How can I rule seven kingdoms if I can't control Slaver's Bay? Why should anyone trust me? Why should anyone follow me?

author: jorah mormont
content: You're a Targaryen. You're the Mother of Dragons.

author: daenerys targaryen
content: I need to be more than that. I will not let those I have freed slide back into chains. I will not sail for Westeros.

author: jorah mormont
content: What, then?

author: daenerys targaryen
content: I will do what queens do. I will rule.

author: petyr baelish
content: Pull up your hood. A memorable shade.

author: sansa stark
content: But how would they know?

author: petyr baelish
content: You know what kind of stories poor men enjoy the most? Ones about rich girls they'll never meet.

author: sansa stark
content: Is this the only way into the Eyrie?

author: petyr baelish
content: The mountains are impassable. If you want to get to the Eyrie, you need to go through the Bloody Gate. It doesn't matter how large your army is, if you attack this gate, you do it on this road, three men abreast and get slaughtered like goats. The first Lords of the Vale didn't have much, but they had these mountains and they knew how to use them. And the fortress they built here has never been overcome. Not once in a thousand years. Know your strengths, use them wisely, and one man can be worth ten thousand.

content: Who would pass the Bloody Gate?

author: petyr baelish
content: Lord Petyr Baelish and his niece, Alayne.

content: Stand to.

content: Welcome back, Lord Baelish.

content: My lord.

content: It's a pleasure to make your acquaintance, Lady Arryn. My name is Al...

content: My flesh and blood.

content: Of course. I understand.

author: lysa

content: I would never say a thing.

author: lysa
content: The Lannisters want to destroy us. They've been trying for years. Now they know what it feels like.

content: Mummy said they killed your mother and they chopped off your brother's head.

author: sansa stark
content: They did, and my father's.

content: They killed my father, too, with poison. I wanted to make the little Lannister baby man fly, but Mother said I couldn't.

author: sansa stark
content: Make him fly?

author: robin
content: Through the Moon Door.

content: And on top of everything else, they made you marry that filthy troll.

content: They did. They made us both. Lord Tyrion didn't want to.

author: lysa
content: I don't believe that for a moment. Did he force himself on you?

author: sansa stark
content: No. We never...

author: lysa
content: Good. Robin, this is your cousin Sansa. But you're not to call her Sansa in front of anyone but Uncle Petyr and myself. Do you understand? Sansa, this is my son Robin.

author: sansa stark
content: It's a pleasure to meet you, Robin.

author: lysa
content: Robin, show Sansa to her chamber. Take the back stairs.

content: Go. We'll speak soon.

author: lysa
content: What took you so long?

author: petyr baelish
content: Arranging for the ascension of King Tommen I, extricating Sansa, getting her here alive.

author: lysa
